<HEAD>ABC Cites Conflict Of Interest in Kissinger News Consultancy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RETRANSMITTING to restore writethru sequence; INSERTS 2 grafs
after 7th, `Had ABC ..., to cite Wall Street Journal report on Kissinger's
business ties to China.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 ABC News would n't have used former Secretary of State <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> as a paid expert on a <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> special last June had it known of his business ties there, a spokeswoman said Friday. However, <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bremer </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> business associate, said there was no conflict of interest in <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON>'s appearance on the broadcast. On it, <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> was asked about possible <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military sanctions against <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> for its violence against the student-led demonstrations in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. In his reply, the former Secretary of State in the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> administrations stressed the importance of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> relations with the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> regime. `` I would n't do any sanctions,'' he told anchor <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>. <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> at the time was appearing under a special agreement with <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> that he terminated Wednesday after his election as a board member of <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> deal, struck in 1982, paid him as a consultant and gave <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> the right to interview him first on any of its broadcasts, including `` World News Tonight'' and <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Koppel </PERSON>'s `` Nightline,'' but only on breaking stories. He was n't paid for appearances as a guest on these shows, including as `` Nightline'' and `` World News Tonight'' when his interviews did n't concern breaking news, said <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Elise </PERSON> <PERSON> Adde </PERSON>. Had ABC News known of his business ties in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, she said, `` we would not have had him on that broadcast'' in June. <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> has extensive business interests in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, including the establishment of a $ 75 million fund to be raised from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> investors for joint ventures with the merchant banking arm of the Chinese government, The Wall Street Journal reported Friday. In addition, his consulting firm <ORGANIZATION> Kissinger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> counsels several businesses on how to conduct operations overseas and, specifically, in their dealings with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, the Journal reported. <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON>'s remarks on the June special were `` not motivated by commercial concerns,'' said <PERSON> Bremer </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> employee for 23 years, now a senior partner in <ORGANIZATION> Kissinger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, an international consulting firm. <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON>'s remarks on issues like the situation in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> last June are solely `` based on what he thinks are the -LRB- <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> -RRB- nation's interest,'' said <PERSON> Bremer </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> deal was not his first with a network news division. He previously had worked for <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s news division after after his White House service. Since 1977, he has been a member of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artists </ORGANIZATION> but under the union's news contract with networks, according union membership rolls. <ORGANIZATION> AFTRA </ORGANIZATION> represents on-air news correspondents and anchors at <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>. The news contract and the entertainers' contract stipulate different pay scales. <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> was busy Friday and was not available for comment, <PERSON> Bremer </PERSON> said. His election to the 14-member CBS board was by a unanimous vote, a source election said Friday. CBS policy is not to comment on internal board matters. As a CBS board member, <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> will paid the same as other board members, $ 22,000 annually, and $ 750 for each meeting he attends, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Schweitzer </PERSON> said. There is no contract that would make <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> exclusive to <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, and his board membership `` has absolutely nothing to do with CBS on-air appearances, `` <PERSON> Schweitzer </PERSON> said. `` In that regard,'' he said, referring to news matters, `` he is <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON>, private citizen and businessman. And he can be interviewed by anyone.''
