<HEAD>U.S. Reported Concerned North Korea Developing Nuclear Arms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is `` gravely concerned'' that communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> may be developing nuclear weapons, the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> news agency <ORGANIZATION> Yonhap </ORGANIZATION> reported from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Friday. It said the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is keeping a close watch on possible efforts in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> to develop nuclear weapons. <ORGANIZATION> Yonhap </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Spencer </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, the head of the department's <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> section, as saying <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> would be as concerned as <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> if <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> produced such weapons. Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> is expected to discuss <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s nuclear capability with Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> at a meeting in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this month, <ORGANIZATION> Yonhap </ORGANIZATION> reported. While denying it has nuclear weapons, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> has repeatedly charged that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces based in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> are equipped with nuclear arms and are preparing for a nuclear war on the divided <LOCATION> Korean </LOCATION> peninsula. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials reject the North Korean claims. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> keeps about 43,000 troops in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> under a defense pact. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is the North's main arms supplier. Chances are dim for an improvement soon in the strained relations between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> despite diplomatic contacts between the two sides in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, the report quoted <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> as saying. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> demands immediate withdrawal of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> says <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces are vital to prevent a North Korean attack. <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> invaded <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> in 1950, setting off the 3-year Korean War. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces intervened on the side of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> and fought under the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> banner. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops have remained in the South ever since.
