<HEAD>In Interview, Benazir Bhutto Says She's Fighting Evil in Pakistan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After 9 -LCB- months as prime minister, <PERSON> Benazir </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> sees herself as a crusader to save <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> from the clutches of drugs, ethnic violence and rancorous politics. `` I see things in terms of knights in shining armor trying to root out evil,'' Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> said in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` That may be a sort of simplistic way to put it, but I am an optimist. I have great dreams for my country and I want to achieve them.'' But she acknowledged her vision might be a bit fanciful. `` I think I am too much of an idealist.'' Educated at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Oxford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, the 36-year-old Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> is the first woman to lead a Moslem nation and as she spoke she had a scarf called a `` dupatta'' draped over her shoulder. When in public she wears the scarf over her head _ the custom of Moslem women _ as a concession to <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s religious right wing, a powerful minority that opposes female rule. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> and her left-leaning <ORGANIZATION> Pakistan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> govern a restless nation of 107 million people burdened by poverty, illiteracy and civil war across the border in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. She said death threats after her government declared war on the heroin trade and drug barons have forced her to think of her safety, something she has resisted since assuming office Dec. 2. `` I do n't believe in a life that is crowded with security,'' she said. `` I think it's kind of nice to be able to slip away, ... after having worked hard for a few days to be able to go for a half an hour walk. `` I just consider it important for a person in public life to try and maintain a sense of normalacy _ to have their feet on the ground.'' As for the drug war, she said, `` We are really now just going after the big people, but it's a much bigger problem. It's just proliferated all over the country like a cancer.'' Western countries estimate that up to 80 percent of the heroin arriving in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> comes from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Drug addiction in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> has soared from near zero in 1979 to an estimated 1 million addicts in 1989. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> is also doing battle with an opposition made up of Islamic fundamentalists, conservatives and loyalists of the late president, Gen. <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> <PERSON> ul-Haq </PERSON>, and his military government. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> overthrew her father, Prime Minister <PERSON> Zulfikar </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>, in a 1977 coup and had him hanged two years later for his alleged complicity in a murder plot. <PERSON> Zia </PERSON>, many of his top generals and <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Raphel </PERSON> died in a mysterious plane crash in August 1988, clearing the way for <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s first free elections in more than a decade and resulting in Mrs. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON>'s election Nov. 16. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> says the most serious threat to her government is ethnic. Hundreds of Pakistanis have died and thousands have been injured since 1986 in violence in her southern home province of <LOCATION> Sindh </LOCATION> in fighting among militant secessionists, Indian Moslem immigrants and internal migrants from poorer provinces. `` During General <PERSON> Zia </PERSON>'s time ethnic groups became very strong,'' she said. `` They set up armed camps and they trained their people, so it's a situation of almost a mini-kind of a guerrilla war. It's not a guerrilla war against the government, but it's almost a state of anarchy and a rebellion against authority. Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> claims that her right-wing political opposition, the nine-party <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, has had a hand in the Sindh violence. She also has implicated neighboring <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> in the Sindh troubles. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> have fought three wars since they became independent from <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in 1947 and they routinely accuse each other of fueling their internal problems. To the west, Ms. <PERSON> Bhutto </PERSON> inherited <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s sponsorship of Moslem guerrillas fighting to oust the Soviet-backed government of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. More than 3 million Afghan war refugees huddle in camps dotting <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>'s western frontier. `` <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> ca n't afford to keep the refugees,'' she said, `` but are the refugees going to go back without political stability? `` So far we have not seen any message or any method that would enable the emergence of an independent <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> or the return of the Afghan refugees. Those remain our goals.'' She also said her political opposition is doomed because of its links to the <PERSON> Zia </PERSON> era, when <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> was under martial law and political parties were barred from elections. `` <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> just ca n't afford a return to the decade of repression,'' she said. `` All those who are patriots in the different sectors of life, whether it is civilian or military, recognize that. Therefore, I see no imminent threat to democracy in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>.'' But she added that law and order can not survive without economic development in a country where the average yearly wage is under $ 400. `` First you've got to try and create a system, create a rule of law which gives security and, side by side, you've got to have economic improvement and opportunitiees so people can -LRB- give -RRB- better meaning -LRB- to -RRB- their lives,'' she said.
