<FIRST>r a BC-FDABribery     09-15 0231</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-FDA Bribery,0236</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pharmaceutical Company Official Sentenced in Generic Drug Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The former president of an <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> generic drug manufacturer who paid $ 32,000 in bribes to three <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> officials has been fined $ 250,000 and ordered to serve a year working for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Dilip </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shah </PERSON>, 43, formerly of <ORGANIZATION> Quad </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pharmaceuticals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, was convicted of bribing <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> officials in exchange for their recommendations for approval of Quad products. In addition to the community service and fine, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hargrove </PERSON> also sentenced <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> on Wednesday to 60 days in jail and imposed two years of probation after the defendant completes his prison time. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> said <PERSON> Shah </PERSON> paid $ 23,000 worth in illegal gratuities to <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Y. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chang </PERSON>, former branch chief of the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s Division of Generic Drugs; $ 8,000 in cash to <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Brancato </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> review chemist; and $ 1,000 in department store gift certificates to <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Kletch </PERSON>, another agency chemist. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> said <PERSON> Shah </PERSON>'s cooperation in the case helped prosecutors convict <PERSON> Kletch </PERSON> and <PERSON> Brancato </PERSON>. <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> also has pleaded guilty in the case. So far, the investigation has resulted in the convictions of the three <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> officials and three pharmaceutical company officials. Two companies also have been found guilty of criminal wrongdoing and are facing heavy fines. <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON> said additional charges are expected as the investigation continues.
