<HEAD>Jewish Settlers Face Problems from Uprising</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIT ARYEH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Jewish settlers in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> say they are trapped between stone-throwing <PERSON> Arabs </PERSON> and an indecisive government. Since the Palestinian uprising began 21 months ago, nails have been strewn on their roads and their cars are targets of stones and firebombs. Glass window panes have been replaced with plastic and travel is often safest in convoy. The settlers complain bitterly that the government is torn on how to put down the uprising and, indeed, on the future of the occupied land itself. The result, they say, is that the army is not doing enough to protect them. `` Of course I am fearful,'' settler <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Barat </PERSON> told visitors to this fenced, hilltop settlement east of <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>. `` If there is debate in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, it undercuts us.'' <PERSON> Barat </PERSON>, 40, a computer scientist, is among more than 70,000 Jews who have moved to the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> since the territories were captured by <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Jordan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war. Some are `` ideological'' settlers, convinced that Jews must reclaim the biblical land of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Others, like <PERSON> Barat </PERSON>, see themselves as part of a front line against a Palestinian state. Still others are lured by the promise of free land and subsidized mortgages. Settlers have become targets in the uprising since many Palestinians see them as one more encroachment on Arab land. Almost half the 1.7 million Palestinians in the territories are refugees whose families fled <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> when it was founded in 1948. The settlers say the army, which recently began deploying extra troops along highways and stepped up escorts for settler convoys at night, still needs to do more. `` Instead of soldiers killing mosquito after mosquito, let them drain the swamp,'' said <PERSON> Kiryat </PERSON> <PERSON> Arba </PERSON> lawyer <PERSON> Eliyakim </PERSON> <PERSON> Haetzni </PERSON>, a leader of the settlers' umbrella group, Gush Emunim, or Bloc of the Faithful. `` We demand the deportation of 5,000 people _ members of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> establishment, stone-throwers and their families _ to show them that stone throwing is not a national sport,'' <PERSON> Haetzni </PERSON> said. `` Arabs must know that they can live here only if we can live here.'' Some Jewish settlers have poisoned Arab vineyards, raided villages and fired on suspected stone throwers, killing at least 23 Palestinians in the past 21 months. Tensions also have increased because of the government's proposal for elections in the territories leading to an interim peace solution. Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> has repeatedly said he will refuse to give up any occupied land, and his right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc urges creation of more Jewish communities in the territories. But the left-leaning <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, partner in the coalition Cabinet with <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION>, advocates trading land for peace and calls for suspending the creation of more settlements if peace talks get under way. The 130 settlements built so far run counter to the U.S.-backed land-for-peace solution, which the Palestinians demand. By far the largest number of settlers live in communities close to the pre-1967 border. Some of the settlements deeper in the territories have populations of only several hundred people. <PERSON> Meron </PERSON> <PERSON> Benvenisti </PERSON>, an Israeli analyst who has studied development in the territories for a decade, notes that more than three-quarters of the settlers live within commuting distance of <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION>. `` They have come to see themselves as suburbanites of the major cities,'' he said. <PERSON> Benvenisti </PERSON> said the settlements depend heavily on government subsidies for survival. He calculates that the government and the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zionist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> have spent $ 2.5 billion in the past 20 years building the new communities, providing basic services like water and roads and resettling Jewish families. Settlers often live rent-free in mobile homes while they build their houses. There is no cost for the land. Mortgages are subsidized, and fees for sewer and water connections are considerably less than in Israeli towns. The goverment plans at least seven new settlements by 1992, but budget constraints have forced the focus of late on trying to increase the population in existing communities. The number of new settlers fell to 4,500 last year from an average of 8,000 in previous years, apparently because of fears over the uprising, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dekel </PERSON>, the prime minister's adviser on settlement affairs. But settlement advocates hope the trend can be reversed. <PERSON> Dekel </PERSON> predicted that the Jewish population in the territories would reach 125,000 in five years, even if the Arab revolt continues. `` People have become used to the uprising,'' he said.
