<HEAD>Ag Department Defends Plan to Boost Wheat Plantings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Commodity analysts in the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> believe wheat farmers wo n't go overboard in signing up for a new option designed to boost 1990 production. The option announced this week by <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> would let a farmer boost plantings by as much as 10 percent from what otherwise would be allowed by the 1990 program. <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> said the increase is needed to help rebuild <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> food stockpiles, including a special `` food security reserve'' to meet global food aid requirements. But some members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> fear production might rise more sharply than <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> projects and push down market prices. And the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wheat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growers </ORGANIZATION> has reservations about the plan. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Penn </PERSON>, assistant deputy administrator for state and county operations in the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stabilization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said the program contains `` some down sides'' that could discourage wheat farmers from planting too much wheat. The 1990 wheat program without the option calls for farmers to idle 5 percent of their base acreage to qualify for price support benefits. This `` acreage reserve'' program feature means farmers can plant wheat on 95 percent of their base. With the option announced by <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>, producers can sign up to plant wheat on more than 95 percent of their land _ up to 105 percent, or 10 percent more than they otherwise would be permitted under the basic 1990 program. But <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> noted for `` every acre that you go over your normal -LRB- base -RRB-, you take an acre cut in the acres eligible for payment'' under the program's target-price formula. Another dampener, he said Thursday in a telephone interview, is that the additional acres will not be counted as planting history for the purpose of adjusting wheat bases in the future. `` So, if you plant 101 percent, you're not going to get credit for that 1 percent as wheat for the purpose of calculating the base for next year,'' <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> said. The signup for 1990 commodity programs will be held January 16 through April 13 at county <ORGANIZATION> ASCS </ORGANIZATION> offices, <LOCATION> Penn </LOCATION> said. Farmers will be able to decide then whether to participate in the optional wheat program. Meanwhile, wheat-state congressmen said the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION>'s decision could weaken prices and hurt producers in some regions. Rep. <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, R-Kan., whose state is the leading wheat producer, said the move could send farmers `` back down the road of low prices and overproduction. Rep. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, R-Ore., complained `` now is not the time to gamble with wheat farmers' income. Although the nation's wheat stockpiles have dropped because of two years of drought, <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> and <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> was overreacting to the lower inventories. `` It's risky, very risky,'' said <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. `` If increased crops do not result in a significant price drop, then wheat farmers might benefit. But that's assuming a lot. Basic laws of supply and demand would dictate that the price could fall.'' <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> option would come too late for some winter wheat producers to alter their planting preparations, especially if they had grown fall-harvested grain sorghum or soybeans after their wheat crop failed earlier this year because of drought. Farmer are planting winter wheat now for harvest next year. It accounts for about three-fourths of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat total. `` Change for the sake of change to this degree is just going to confuse farmers and irritate them, to say the least. And it's done just that,'' said <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat carryover at the beginning of the current marketing year on June 1 was about 694 million bushels, down from 1.261 billion bushels on June 1, 1988, and 1.821 billion bushels on June 1, 1987. According to <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> projections, the carryover may be down to 494 million bushels by next June 1. Despite a larger harvest this year, demand for wheat continues to outstrip production. Department analysts say the 1990 option is expected to boost the acreage for harvest by 2.1 million acres to an estimated 69.6 million acres. As a result, they say, the 1990 harvest would rise only 66 million bushels to 2.596 billion bushels. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wheat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Growers </ORGANIZATION> was less critical of the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> announcement, but association president <PERSON> Reggie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyckoff </PERSON> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> export efforts should be stepped up if plantings increase. Producers `` want to be assured that they wo n't be caught holding a mountain of surplus grain if this experiment fails,'' <PERSON> Wyckoff </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Genoa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, wheat farmer, said in a statement issued by the association's <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> office.
