<HEAD>East Germans Bring Pollution to West Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIRARD C. STEICHEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASSAU, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of East German refugees have driven into this country in a cloud of pollution from their tiny, exhaust-belching cars. The East German Trabants have two cylinders and run on a mixture of gasoline and oil. The cars do not meet <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s strict emission control laws, and the environmental Green party says one should be put in a museum with a sign: `` Forest Killer'' and the rest sent to the scrap heap. West German transportation officials have been issuing special permits to allow the East Germans to drive the rickety plastic-and-fiberglass cars. But the <ORGANIZATION> Greens </ORGANIZATION> object to a plan by the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> to give wholesale exemptions to the new drivers. Instead, they say the government should hand out annual federal railway passes, worth about $ 4,000 each, in exchange for the Trabants. `` We're going to have to come up with some imaginative solutions to this problem,'' said <PERSON> Erhard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jauck </PERSON>, a spokesman for the Bavarian <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>. East Germans typically wait more than 11 years for a Trabant and more than 14 years for the larger <ORGANIZATION> Wartburg </ORGANIZATION> sedans some refugees drive. But after they become established in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, most refugees probably will get rid of their cars. Some will do so for reasons other than pollution, however. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> is surrounded by East German territory, and many of the refugees who want to settle in the city are reluctant to drive their car _ which still carry East German license plates _ 70 miles across their homeland to reach <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
