<HEAD>Hispanics Most Likely to Drop Out of School</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TAMARA HENRY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The high school dropout rate for Hispanics is nearing `` a national tragedy,'' says Education Secretary <PERSON> Lauro </PERSON> <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> who points to a new study showing dropout rates for other students have fallen in the last decade. <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> said the study released Thursday by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> disputes the popular perception that overall dropout rates have been rising. But he said statistics on Hispanics are troubling because they show one-third of all Hispanics aged 16 to 24 were not enrolled in school and were not high school graduates last year. The report, `` Dropout Rates in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>: 1988,'' showed 4.4 percent of students in grades 10 through 12 dropped out of high school annually in the years 1985-1988, down from 6.6 percent in 1978. Nearly 13 percent of all 16 - to 24-year-olds were not in school and had not completed school last year, down from 16 percent in 1968 `` While the report shows some progress,'' <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> said, `` I find much in it alarming. The nation can not rest any easier based upon our findings. `` As of 1988, 4.2 million young adults were without a high school diploma. While overall rates may be down slightly, ... for our Hispanic population, the dropout problem is a national tragedy. One-third of Hispanic young adults were not high school graduates in 1988,'' said <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON>, the first Hispanic to head the department. Overall, the dropout rates were 15 percent for whites, 22 percent for blacks and 28 percent for Hispanics. The majority of dropouts are whites, who accounted for 66 percent of all young adults without diplomas. The dropout rates for American Indians and Alaskan natives were 35 percent, while those for <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> students were 8 percent. <PERSON> Cavazos </PERSON> said the `` glimmer of hope in the report is that the disparity between white and black students has narrowed.'' The report showed dropout rates for whites and blacks are similar when individual and family backgrounds are taken into account, such as the rates for blacks and whites living in central cities and those living in suburbs. The center tracked a sample of students who were high school sophomores in 1980 and found 17 percent had not graduated by 1982. However, 46 percent of these dropouts had completed school by 1986. The study was required by the <ORGANIZATION> Hawkins-Stafford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Secondary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> Improvement Amendments of 1988.
