<SECOND>PM-New Destroyer,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shipbuilder Says Destroyer is Ready to Launch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pentagon officials and the manufacturer of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s new $ 1.2 billion destroyer are disputing charges the ship is a `` procurement nightmare'' of cost overruns and schedule delays. `` The ship is ready in every respect to be launched,'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Haggett </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Bath </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION>, said Thursday. <PERSON> Haggett </PERSON> spoke after Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on oversight and investigations, wrote the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> complaining the program is 18 months behind schedule and the DDG-51 destroyer that Bath Iron Works will launch Saturday is only 38 percent complete `` The ship has suffered huge overruns, with the design costs increasing by about 120 percent; and construction costs have increased by more than 60 percent,'' <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> said in a Sept. 12 letter to <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Garrett </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. Hailed as the world's most advanced surface combat ship, the guided-missile destroyer is designed with a more expensive all-steel superstructure instead of one that was part aluminum and more prone to splintering and fire damage. It will be equipped with sophisticated Aegis computers and Tomahawk cruise missiles. According to <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>'s letter, design costs have increased from the original contract estimate of $ 111 million to $ 247 million and construction costs have grown from $ 157 million to $ 252 million. A total of 760 change orders have been made, he said. One involved the combat system and included 44 modifications to the original ship design requiring revisions to 30 to 40 percent of the ship's drawings. <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> based his charges on a draft report from the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, which is conducting an inquiry into the program. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>'s final report is expected later this year. `` The acquisition of the DDG-51 has turned into a procurement nightmare,'' <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> said in the letter. <PERSON> Haggett </PERSON> called <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>'s assessment a `` distortion of the overall picture on the destroyer program'' and `` factually incorrect.'' <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Cmdr. <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said the service `` considers the program well under control in both cost and schedule.'' `` This launching represents the normal progression in the construction, equipment activation and test plan. The remaining work on the ship requires the ship to be afloat,'' <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said in a statement. According to <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, the production schedule calls for the ship to be delivered in February 1991. The original delivery date of October 1989 was changed due to a 99-day strike at Bath Iron Works in 1985, a requirement of additional <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> testing of the combat system and problems with computer-aided design. <PERSON> Haggett </PERSON> said the DDG-51 is `` 47 to 51 percent complete, a higher level than we launched our previous prototype ship.'' He disputed <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>'s total of 760 change orders, saying the actual number is less than 300. <PERSON> Haggett </PERSON> also questioned <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>'s claim that the company has petitioned the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> for an $ 85 million bailout or threatened to go bankrupt. `` We repeatedly told the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> that this company is financially viable,'' <PERSON> Haggett </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from Bath, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> also said Bath Iron Works, despite four years of work on the design and construction of the destroyer, still has not supplied the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> with a validated design and production drawings. `` The design is in excellent condition. We have over 3,000 drawings,'' <PERSON> Haggett </PERSON> said. Rep. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on seapower and strategic and critical materials, played down the charges raised by <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> `` I do n't see anything very scandalous,'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said in an interview. `` It still will be the best ship of its class in the world.''
