<FIRST>r w PM-BlackCaucus     09-15 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Black Caucus,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Black Caucus Celebrates its Success</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Black members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> _ who in 20 years have moved from outsiders demanding black power to insiders wielding it _ are celebrating their successes this week while considering how best to use a $ 2 million war chest. The money, much of it raised from corporate donors, was not on the formal agenda for the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION>' annual `` Legislative Weekend'' that opened Thursday and runs through Saturday night. But it was a matter of behind-the-scenes debate among the 23 blacks who are members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, as they were joined by thousands of black political elite from around the country for the gala fund-raiser, social event and policy discussion. Rep. <PERSON> Kweisi </PERSON> <PERSON> Mfume </PERSON>, a second-term Democrat representing <LOCATION> Baltimore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, who adopted an African name, said the 23 black members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> are considering several proposals for spending the money. Among them are to establish a think tank doing black-oriented research, a recruitment center aimed at developing black political candidates, and even a computerized library on African-American culture. `` We ought to make ourselves more effective'' with the money, <PERSON> Mfume </PERSON> said. A $ 300-a-plate black-tie dinner Saturday night is expected to attract 4,000 guests, and more than 20,000 people will participate in related events, including a black fashion show and numerous parties. The <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION> is hosting the three-day session at a time when black political leaders have successes to celebrate, such as the victory in Tuesday's <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> mayoral primary of black candidate <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Dinkins </PERSON>, and the candidacy in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> of <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> nominee <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilder </PERSON>, who seeks to become the first black elected governor. Blacks in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> are enjoying unprecedented power, too. Much of it is the result of advances through the seniority system that awards power to the most veteran members _ the same system that once benefited white Southern conservatives who were re-elected with little opposition time after time. Their numbers have grown since the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION> was formed in 1970, when there were 13 members. But more importantly, caucus members now hold the chairmanships of five House committees and 18 subcommittees, and young black newcomers are working their way up some of the most influential congressional committees. `` The staying power of their members and the number of chairmanships that they have make them an effective force,'' said former Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, who is white. One member, Rep. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON>, D-Pa., has leapfrogged ahead, serving last term as <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> chairman and winning the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Democrats' No 3 leadership position this year as majority whip. The rise in power is limited to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, however. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has no black members. The number of blacks in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has at least temporarily declined with the death in an African plane crash last month of Rep. <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Leland </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Leland </PERSON> was mourned at several of the caucus' opening events President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> earlier this year hosted the caucus at the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> _ its first invitation there in eight years. In addition to the chance to discuss issues, members estimate this year's Legislative Weekend event will raise $ 1 million for the <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, a legally separate entity with interlocking board members. With corporations donating sums of $ 50,000 in some cases, income in recent years has exceeded spending on fellowships, internships and scholarships, allowing the foundation to purchase its own building and to accumulate a reserve of just over $ 2 million, according to foundation financial records for the year ending Dec. 31, 1988. Another issue under debate by black members involves whether the caucus should continue accepting large contributions to the foundation from tobacco companies and liquor manufacturers, which some members feel are contributing to health problems within the black community. The caucus lists companies including <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Anheuser-Busch </ORGANIZATION>, Courvoisier Cognac VSOP, <ORGANIZATION> Stroh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brewery </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Seagram </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> among its major contributors.
</TEXT>
