<HEAD>Broadcasters Oppose ESPN Exclusive Baseball Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Broadcasters are taking aim at the <ORGANIZATION> ESPN </ORGANIZATION> cable network in a new campaign to preserve free, over-the-air televised sports. Viewers `` are getting something now for free that in the future, if the tide goes the way it has, they are going to have to pay for,'' says <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Berkery </PERSON>, an executive of <ORGANIZATION> WSBK-TV </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> ESPN </ORGANIZATION> earlier this year snagged a four-year, $ 400 million contract with <ORGANIZATION> Major </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baseball </ORGANIZATION> to carry games on Wednesday and Sunday nights. Outraged broadcasters were shut out, and they said Thursday they are going to fight _ on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> if necessary. Television executives from stations with baseball broadcast rights in 24 of the 26 <ORGANIZATION> Major </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baseball </ORGANIZATION> cities said they will meet with <ORGANIZATION> ESPN </ORGANIZATION> and major league officials to demand access to Wednesday and Sunday games, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Serrao </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stations </ORGANIZATION>. `` An immediate effort will be made to seek the elimination of the exclusive restrictions on the Wednesday and Sunday night blackouts,'' <PERSON> Serrao </PERSON> said. `` These blackouts on free, over-the-air TV are contrary to the public interest.'' Local TV stations that already had contracted with individual baseball teams to carry a certain number of games during the season now have no access to Wednesdays and Sundays, the station executives said. Meanwhile, regional cable sports networks can show the games, the executives said. Local broadcasters have no legal recourse because <ORGANIZATION> Major </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baseball </ORGANIZATION> agreements supersede contracts made by individual teams, <PERSON> Berkery </PERSON> said. The same situation applies when college athletic conferences such as the Big 10 and <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> 10 make cable agreements that override contracts between individual schools and local broadcasters, <ORGANIZATION> INTV </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> <PERSON> Padden </PERSON> said. Officials at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> were out of the office and not available for comment Thursday. But the <ORGANIZATION> NCTA </ORGANIZATION> has said that local broadcasters are showing 40 percent more professional baseball games now than in 1975, and that cable is not siphoning away free TV sports. Major League Baseball spokesman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Levin </PERSON>, reached by telephone in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> where team owners are meeting, would not comment on the broadcasters' allegations. The broadcasters said they will urge <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to hold hearings `` to investigate the alarming siphoning of sports from free, over-the-air television.'' They said they were given assurances in meetings with Sens. <PERSON> Arlen </PERSON> <PERSON> Specter </PERSON>, R-Pa., and <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, D-Tenn., that their concerns will be heard on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> told the broadcasters he will seek hearings this fall on his bill to reregulate the cable TV industry and on other cable TV bills now pending, <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Marla </PERSON> <PERSON> Romash </PERSON> said later. `` One of Senator <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>'s concerns is the flight of athletics from free TV to pay TV,'' <PERSON> Romash </PERSON> said, noting that there is no pending legislation that specifically addresses that issue. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> is a member of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> subcommittee </ORGANIZATION>, and <PERSON> Specter </PERSON> is on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> antitrust, monopolies and business rights subcommittee. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Craig </PERSON>, executive assistant to Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Hawaii </LOCATION>, chairman of the communications subcommittee, said, `` I do n't see a stand-alone -LRB- sports -RRB- hearing, but certainly during the cable oversight hearings you're bound to get some hard questioning on the migration of sports.''
