<BYLINE>Critics Say Federal Study Denies Many Diabetics ^By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A government study in which expensive orthopedic shoes will be bought for some diabetic Medicare patients but not others is being criticized for jeopardizing health in the name of medical economics. `` I consider it morally reprehensible'' to not provide the shoes to some diabetics at high risk of foot amputations, said <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Matek </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Podiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. But project staff members say no one is being denied anything. Rather, some Medicare recipients are getting something extra and that the benefits of the study will reach all such patients, they say. Under the study that began last month, <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> is choosing 27,000 diabetic patients in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> who have a high risk of hospitalization or amputation because of circulatory problems in their feet. Half will be reimbursed for up to $ 305 for a pair of therapeutic shoes or inserts, but the other half will not, though they can still buy the footwear. The idea is to determine if the government would save money in the long run by providing shoes to such patients. About 20,000 diabetics each year have parts of their legs and feet removed. Many experts say specially-fitted shoes have been shown to prevent the problems that lead to amputations. <PERSON> Matek </PERSON> said he finds it `` morally unacceptable to deny a recognizably beneficial intervention to one out of every two people at high risk for amputation.'' And he says since Medicare patients in the study who are not reimbursed can still buy the shoes, there's no point in doing a cost-effectiveness comparison. But <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Wooldridge </PERSON>, project director at <LOCATION> Mathematica </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Princeton </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, health policy study group commissioned by the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> to do the study, dismisses the ethical concerns as illogical. `` They interpret it as someone being denied something. But no one is going to be denied anything. Some are going to receive something extra,'' she said. The legislation that called for the study says the benefit will not go into effect if the study shows money would not be saved in the long run by paying for the shoes. <PERSON> Wooldridge </PERSON> and others in all likelihood therapeutic footwear for diabetics will become a covered <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> benefit, at least by 1993. The bill originally made the shoes a covered benefit but got caught in the budget squeeze after the stock market crash in October 1987. Backers in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> compromised to save the bill by calling for a study to verify claims it would save $ 25 million a year by avoiding costly hospitalizations and amputations. <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Trieger </PERSON>, director of the division of health systems and special studies in <ORGANIZATION> HCFA </ORGANIZATION>'s office of demonstrations, said, `` when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> says do a demonstration, that means there will be certain people who get the benefit and certain people who do n't.'' About 2,500 podiatrists and other physicians in the three states have expressed willingness to participate so far. Dr. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Meritt </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, podiatrist who is president of the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Podiatric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said he will participate in the study, though he is concerned patients who need the shoes will hold off buying them until they find out whether <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> will pay for them. `` I'm going to recommend that they get the shoe'' regardless of whether the government will pay, he said. `` I do n't want my patients waiting on the government. That could be hazardous, and that concerns me.''
