 Misgivings about <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy toward <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> have surfaced in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in anticipation of the promised withdrawal of Vietnamese forces from the <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> country later this month. Several Congressmen accused the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration Thursday of taking a weak stand at the recent international conference on <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> against return of the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, the communists accused of causing more than a million Cambodian deaths during their 1975-78 `` Killing Fields'' rule over <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. `` Given the moral consequences of failure _ given the possibility that the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> may return ... if there was ever an issue in which consultation between the executive branch and <ORGANIZATION> congress </ORGANIZATION> is an absolute necessity, this is the one,'' Rep. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-NY </LOCATION>, told his <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Asian-Pacific affairs subcommittee after a public hearing on the issue. Spectators were then cleared from the room to enable a senior <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official to clarify in closed session the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> strategy for blocking the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> from returning to power. The official, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for East Asian and <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> affairs, during the public debate blasted as `` grossly unfair and inaccurate, implications that somehow we are trying to whitewash what happened during the 1970s'' in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> said he wou