s </LOCATION> acquiesced. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> position meant that `` we are clinging to the outmoded policies and paranoia of the Vietnam War, but the war is over and the world has changed. We are not able by sheer force and strong will to create a <LOCATION> Cambodian </LOCATION> government that is absolutely to our liking,'' <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> said. `` If stopping the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> `` means taking a fresh, more reasoned assessment of the successes of the -LRB- Vietnam-installed -RRB- <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> government, then so be it.'' Rep. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Leach </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Iowa </LOCATION>, said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` does not have the luxury'' of avoiding such moral issues as <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> `` genocide.'' He said <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Pol </PERSON> <PERSON> Pot </PERSON> should be tried by an international court for war crimes. <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> negotiations are in suspension and could be resumed if progress appears likely after six months of lower-level talks. He blamed failure to achieve a comprehensive settlement at <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON>, head of the Vietnamese-installed government in <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>. They refused to compromise on <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON>'s four-party formula and sought to retain the infrastructure of the <PERSON> Hun </PERSON> <PERSON> Sen </PERSON> government, giving it unfair advantage in promised elections, he said. <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> `` is not infallible ... he is capable of monumental misjudgment,'' <PERSON> Solarz </PERSON> said. He recalled that the prince's alliance with the <