<HEAD>Pentagon Drops Missile Supplier</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 7th graf to change `Friday' to `today'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> says the firing of a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> defense contractor will delay deployment of new <ORGANIZATION> Amraam </ORGANIZATION> air-to-air missiles and force the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> to take parts from old missiles until a new supplier begins production. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday it dropped <ORGANIZATION> Micronics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brea </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, because of years of problems with an arming and safety device on air-to-air missiles. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> withdrew its inspectors from the <ORGANIZATION> Micronics </ORGANIZATION> plant near <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and the government no longer will accept delivery of the safety and arming device, said Lt. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Fallon </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. `` There's no evidence that the safety and arming device has caused any detrimental missile performance,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has a full inventory of missiles for its operational forces to compensate for an expected stop in deliveries of the safety and arming device.'' The devices will be produced by <ORGANIZATION> Raymond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, starting in 1991. The missile itself is built by the <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> unit of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The troubled device will cause problems with the <ORGANIZATION> Amraam </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Sparrow </PERSON> and Sidewinder missiles, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported in today's editions The <ORGANIZATION> Amraam </ORGANIZATION> will not be installed aboard <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> F-15 and <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> F-18 fighters until new parts are secured from another source, but production problems for the Sparrow and Sidewinder are expected to be relatively minor. The arming device, roughly comparable to the safety on a gun, is built into the missile's fuze to prevent premature firing of the missile. It also prevents explosions in accidents, such as dropping a warhead on a carrier deck, but allows the warhead to explode when it hits a target after being fired. Limited production of the <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> missile began eight years ago, but as late as three years ago the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> disclosed it was not deploying the weapon because of several problems, including the arming device. In a `` tear-down'' inspection of the missile in mid-1986, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> found 2,694 defects. Last year, the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> reported the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> was conducting a criminal investigation of <ORGANIZATION> Micronics </ORGANIZATION>, which was suspected of using a production process that does not yield the quality required by specifications for the arming device. The radar-guided <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> was designed for the F-14 fighter and is supposed to be able to hit targets 100 miles away.
