<HEAD>After Ethiopian Talks, Next Stop for Carter: Nicaragua</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former President <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, fresh from sponsoring talks to end a rebellion in <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, is off to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> to prepare for elections that could lead to a definitive end to that country's war. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, whose activities in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> this year have given him a more visible role in world affairs than at any time since he left the White House in 1981, will use the visit to prepare for his role as an observer of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s Feb. 25 presidential elections. Peace talks that began Sept. 7 between the <LOCATION> Ethiopian </LOCATION> government and the <ORGANIZATION> Eritrean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> may conclude today or adjourn until Tuesday, when <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> returns from <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, said center spokeswoman <PERSON> Carrie </PERSON> <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON>. Acting as a private citizen, though with the blessing of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> has used his public policy facility and think tank as a force to boost talks to end various regional conflicts. In <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, as in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> will be representing the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freely </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elected </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heads </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION>, a group of current and former democratically elected chiefs of state. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> was an observer at the May elections in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. Afterwards, his accusations of fraud against de-facto military leader Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> received widespread attention. Over the past two weeks, <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> has served as host and observer for preliminary discussions aimed at setting an agenda for talks to end the 28-year-old war between <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> and the Eritrean rebels in the Horn of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` I think I can say without contradiction from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> that they do indeed support my trip to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> told reporters in a briefing during the Ethiopian talks. `` But I will emphasize again, this is not a duty designated to me by the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration.'' <PERSON> Harmon </PERSON> said <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s visit this weekend will include meetings with members of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, government officials, opposition leaders and representatives of church and civic groups. President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> is expected to run for re-election in election against <PERSON> Violeta </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrios </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON>, the director of the opposition newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> and candidate of the 14-party opposition coalition. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said his continued involvement in world matters is being conducted by a concerned citizen, not by a man interested in resurrecting a political career. `` You know, I've got a lot of things I could be doing,'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> told reporters last week, using the Ethiopia-Eritrea talks as an example. `` And I do n't have any personal thing to gain from spending days or weeks or whatever trying to bring peace to the people of <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION>. `` But I look upon this as one of the most terrible conflicts in the world, and the fact that both sides are at least going to have good-faith negotiations has already been proven to me ... and I think warrants my investment of time,'' <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said.
