<HEAD>Syrian-Christian Clashes Shatter Optimism</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Residents rushed back to basement bomb shelters today when <LOCATION> Syrian </LOCATION> and Christian gunners shelled the city hours after <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> mediators concluded talks aimed at ending the fighting. Police said five people were killed and seven wounded in the exchanges, which occurred residential districts in the city's Moslem and <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> sectors as well as the wooded mountains southeast of the capital. The latest casualties raised the toll to 900 killed and 2,559 wounded since March 8, when the current round of violence broke out pitting Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s mainly Christian troops against Syrian and allied forces. The duel started shortly after the foreign ministers of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> ended two days of talks in the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Red </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Jiddah </LOCATION> late Thursday without issuing a cease-fire call. The three ministers, in a brief statement, said only that they conducted a `` necessary evaluation'' of the situation in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and considered the possibility of new moves. The statement said King Fahd of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> II of <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION> and Algerian President <PERSON> Chadli </PERSON> <PERSON> Bendjedid </PERSON> will release an official statement Saturday about the outcome of the committee's efforts The Syrian-Christian duel forced the few citizens remaining in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> to rush to basements and underground shelters to escape the barrage, shattering hopes that a relative lull in the fighting would continue. The exchanges had sharply diminished Thursday and Wednesday while the <ORGANIZATION> Arab </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> members met. Local newspapers had predicted a cease-fire in the confrontation between <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s 20,000 soldiers and the 40,000 Syrian troops. `` We were under the impression that this -LRB- shelling -RRB- was over, at least for the time being,'' said <PERSON> Rashid </PERSON> <PERSON> Makkouk </PERSON>, a Sunni Moslem resident of west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Bourj </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Abu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Haidar </LOCATION> district. After hearing the talks produced no agreement, <PERSON> Makkouk </PERSON> said at the entrance to his shell-scarred apartment building, `` I was wondering whether we should return to the shelter when the explosion of the first shell echoed. We rushed down.'' The shelling began in March over a blockade by <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> of illegal ports run by <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>'s militia allies south of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> sought to reimpose government control on the ports. Syrian and allied forces retaliated by shelling and besieging the 310-square-mile Christian enclave, <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON>'s power base northeast of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>.
