y establish elaborate processing procedures when no one will be admitted anyway? <PERSON> Jewel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lafontant </PERSON>, the administration's coordinator for refugee affairs, told panel members that, `` we share your frustration. We do n't have all the answers, but we're working darned hard to find them.'' Two pending bills would require the administration to automatically grant refugee status to all Soviet emigres on the grounds that they face persecution as a group. All Soviets were granted refugee status until summer 1988, when former attorney general <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> ordered that each applicant be required to prove persecution on an individual basis. This change resulted in 20 to 50 percent of applicants being turned down, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials said Thursday. <PERSON> Berman </PERSON> released an internal <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report that said widespread anti-Semitism in the lower ranks of Soviet government and among the general populace has increased greatly under glasnost. State-sponsored anti-Semitism, official policy for hundreds of years, has abated, although many cases are still reported, the report said. The Jewish community expressed its concern with the new administration strategy at separate White House and State Department meetings. At the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, leaders of five American Jewish groups gave the administration the names of 400 Jewish families who have been denied exit permits. The issue will be discussed later this month in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> when Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> meets with Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>. Also on the <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> agenda is a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> request to increase its embassy staff in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> to deal with the number of Soviet applicants seeking entry into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The administration's new proposal would provide full federal sponsorship for 40,000 Soviet refugees while private organizations would finance the resettlement for the remaining 10,000. It also would allow as many as 30,000 Soviets to come here under a special parole category if they can find the money for their travel and resettlement. To save money, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced it will close processing centers for Soviet emigres in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, and handle all processing in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> with a new facility in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> to help with the caseload.
