<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Dolores </PERSON> <PERSON> Ibarruri </PERSON>, the Spanish Communist leader who became a legend during the Civil War, was seriously ill in a <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> hospital today, one day after being admitted for treatment of pneumonia, doctors said. Mrs. <PERSON> Ibarruri </PERSON>, 93, checked into <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> y Cajal hospital on Thursday after complaining of serious breathing problems. Doctors today said her condition had improved slightly overnight but remained serious because of her advanced age and chronic blood circulation problems. Mrs. <PERSON> Ibarruri </PERSON>, better known by her pen-name `` La Pasionaria,'' was one of the Spanish <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s founders in 1920 and is currently the party's honorary president. During the 1931-39 Second Republic, she was elected to <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and became renowned during the 1936-39 Civil War for her fiery radio broadcasts exhorting Republican forces to defeat Gen. <PERSON> Francisco </PERSON> <PERSON> Franco </PERSON>'s insurgent army rebels. During the 1937 rebel siege of <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>, her defiant phrase _ `` no pasaran'' or `` they shall not pass'' _ became the battle cry of loyalist Republican forces. Mrs. <PERSON> Ibarruri </PERSON> entered politics as a labor organizer and strike leader and wrote newspaper articles signed `` La Pasionaria,'' which is the Spanish transalation for passion flower but can also mean `` The Passionate One.'' She chose the name because her first article appeared in 1916 in a <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> newspaper during Holy Week, or Semana de la Pasion in Spanish. After the war, she spent 38 years in exile in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and received that country's highest civilian award, the Order of <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>. She returned to live in the <LOCATION> Spanish </LOCATION> capital at the age of 82 as <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> made a peaceful transition to democracy after <PERSON> Franco </PERSON>'s death in 1975. In 1977, in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>'s first democratic elections since the war, the white-haired grandmother won back her deputy's seat in the lower house of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, though she later gave it up because of worsening health.
