<HEAD>13 Killed in Hindu-Moslem Riot; 12 Slain in Punjab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police opened fire on rioting Hindus and Moslems in a western Indian town, and at least 13 people were killed and more than 50 injured, news reports said today. In northern <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> state, meanwhile, police today blamed Sikh extremists for an attack that killed 12 people in renewed violence Thursday night, including eight members of one family. The clashes in the western town of <LOCATION> Kota </LOCATION>, 250 miles southwest of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>, came late Thursday during celebrations to mark the end of a popular Hindu festival, Press Trust of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> said. Moslems hurled stones at marchers carrying idols of a Hindu god, leading to clashes in which `` arms were freely used,'' the reports said. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> India </ORGANIZATION> said police first tried to repulse the rioters with batons, but the crowds hurled rocks at policemen, forcing them to open fire. The news agencies did not say if the deaths resulted from police firing or the clashes. More than 25 shops were burned and a shop selling arms was looted, <ORGANIZATION> PTI </ORGANIZATION> said. It is not known if stolen weapons were used in the fighting. A curfew was imposed and troops patrolled the streets today, the reports said. In <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION>, six militants armed with automatic assault rifles raided the farmhouse in the village of <LOCATION> Rasoolpur </LOCATION>, killing eight family members, said <PERSON> Surjit </PERSON> <PERSON> Singh </PERSON>, a senior district police official. Elsewhere Thursday night, Sikh militants were reported to have killed four other people. The militants, believed to belong to the radical <ORGANIZATION> Khalistan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commando </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>, escaped, police said. The <ORGANIZATION> Khalistan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commando </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> is one of about a dozen militant groups operating in the troubled northwestern state, where more than 1,280 people have been killed this year. Since 1982, Sikh militants have been demanding a separate state, claiming discrimination by the Hindu majority. <LOCATION> Sikhism </LOCATION> was founded as an branch from <LOCATION> Hinduism </LOCATION> and Islam in the 16th century. Sikhs comprise less than 2 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s population Hindus make up more than 80 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 880 million people.
