<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has given Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> the authority to released an additional 2 million metric tons of emergency wheat for use as food aid to distressed areas of the world. The White House announcement Thursday said the wheat could be used to provide `` emergency food assistance to developing countries'' that run short of domestic supplies. Under the Food Security Wheat Reserve Act of 1980, a stockpile of 4 million tons _ about 147 million bushels _ was created for use to supply emergency food relief abroad. The first time the stockpile was tapped was last October when President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> authorized release of 1.5 million tons when it became apparent there would not be enough wheat in the marketplace to fill the needs of developing countries. With the authorization to use an additional 2 million tons, the special reserve is virtually depleted. That was one reason <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> gave earlier this week when he announced a liberalization of the government's 1990 wheat program _ to help rebuild <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> stockpiles, including the special reserve.
