/PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mich </LOCATION>., expressed strong reservations with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposed cap on future emissions of sulfur dioxide, the chief ingredient of acid The limit would make it difficult for utilities, the main source of acid rain, to grow and take on new customers, <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON> argued. <PERSON> Baucus </PERSON> said his legislation would tighten tailpipe standards for autos, with the goal of cutting car pollution in half by the year 2000. But it would not force use of clean-burning motor vehicle fuels in severely polluted cities. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration calls its clean fuels program the `` most innovative and far-reaching component'' of its ozone-cutting proposals. The administration would force a portion of the car fleet in the most seriously polluted cities to operate on clean burning fuels such as methanol, ethanol, natural gas, electricity, propane or reformulated gasoline. The president wants a sale schedule for such vehicles, beginning with 500,000 cars sold nationally in the 1995 model year, and going up to one million cars in the model years 1997 through 2004. The <PERSON> Baucus </PERSON> proposal would give automakers discretion in deciding how to reduce car pollution, and hand them the option of using clean fuels or other methods. `` I do n't think it's wise to mandate change in the marketplace so that certain users have to use certain kinds of cars,'' <PERSON> Baucus </PERSON> said.
