<HEAD>A Revival of `Sweeney Todd' Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs with what other critics said. No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Sweeney Todd'' is <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Sondheim </PERSON>'s most relentless and uncompromising musical, a brilliant but chilling tale of revenge. That chill permeated the original 1979 production _ from demonic performances by <PERSON> Len </PERSON> <PERSON> Cariou </PERSON> and <PERSON> Angela </PERSON> <PERSON> Lansbury </PERSON> to <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Prince </PERSON>'s Brechtian direction to the mammoth, black iron-foundry sets of <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> and <PERSON> Franne </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> Now, in an intimate revival which opened Thursday at Broadway's Circle in the Square, director <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON> has sought to humanize, if not soften, the story and its leading characters The change makes for a remarkable reworking of what is still the most unnerving musical ever to reach Broadway. This is a much more personal `` Sweeney Todd'' than the original, which seemed, at times, to be more an indictment of the Industrial Revolution for what it had done to British society than the story of real people. Sorrow and even a little pity for <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> and his cohorts creep into the bloodthirsty goings-on at the Circle in the Square. That's something the brutal but effective original production did n't allow <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Wheeler </PERSON>'s underrated book, taken from an adaptation by British playwright <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Bond </PERSON>, seems better than it was 10 years ago. A model of compression, it tells of <PERSON> Todd </PERSON>, a barber who returns to <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> after an unjust exile and imprisonment in <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. He finds his wife gone and his daughter the ward of the lascivious Judge <PERSON> Turpin </PERSON>. <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> plots revenge with the help of Mrs. <PERSON> Lovett </PERSON>, a dotty maker of meat pies. The barber slits the throats of his customers, and their corpses provide fresh ingredients for Mrs. <PERSON> Lovett </PERSON>'s delicacies. Much of what <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON> has accomplished has been dictated by the in-the-round playing area. The show began life last spring at the <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>, a tiny off-off-Broadway troupe which uses an East Side school gymnasium for its productions. On Broadway, the director and set designer <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Morgan </PERSON> surround the audience with scenery. A panorama of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> tenements of the late 19th century covers the theater's walls. So do clotheslines of drying laundry. At one end of the stage sprawls Mrs. <PERSON> Lovett </PERSON>'s pie shop and at the other the home of Judge <PERSON> Turpin </PERSON>. In between, the cobblestone streets of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> become the arena for much of the crowd action. A fog machine works overtime to create the right smoky atmosphere. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Gunton </PERSON>'s portrayal of the title character echoes the <PERSON> Len </PERSON> <PERSON> Cariou </PERSON> original. His voice may not be as strong as <PERSON> Cariou </PERSON>'s, but his acting has more range. There are more changes in the character of Mrs. <PERSON> Lovett </PERSON>, seen here as a woman willing to do anything for love rather than the grotesque comic figure so wonderfully portrayed by <PERSON> Lansbury </PERSON>. <PERSON> Beth </PERSON> <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON> is a softer, giddier Mrs. <PERSON> Lovett </PERSON> than her predecessor. She's also a better singer and gives a sweeter emphasis to such comic songs as `` By the Sea'' and `` The Worst Pies in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Sondheim </PERSON>'s monumental score is a study in contrasts. Haunting melodies such as `` Not While I'm Around,'' `` <PERSON> Johanna </PERSON>'' and `` Pretty Woman'' clash with much harsher numbers such as `` The Ballad of <PERSON> Sweeney </PERSON> <PERSON> Todd </PERSON>,'' `` Epiphany'' and `` City on Fire.'' The supporting cast must grapple with some of the most difficult songs in the show. There are expert portraits and some notable singing by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Barron </PERSON> as the evil judge and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarty </PERSON> as the porcine <PERSON> Beadle </PERSON>. Also turning in fine work are <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Walton </PERSON> as <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON>, the young sailor in love with <PERSON> Todd </PERSON>'s daughter <PERSON> Johanna </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Korbich </PERSON> as <PERSON> Tobias </PERSON>, Mrs. <PERSON> Lovett </PERSON>'s young assistant in the pie shop. <PERSON> Korbich </PERSON> delivers a touching version of `` Not While I'm Around,'' the lullaby <PERSON> Tobias </PERSON> sings to Mrs. <PERSON> Lovett </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Nabel </PERSON> misses the comedy of <ORGANIZATION> Pirelli </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Todd </PERSON>'s ill-fated Italian competitor, and <PERSON> Gretchen </PERSON> <PERSON> Kingsley </PERSON> as <PERSON> Johanna </PERSON> sings harshly. `` Sweeney Todd'' originally succeeded as a large-scale combination of Grand Guignol and melodrama. It was a horror story that did n't allow the audience to get close to the characters. By reducing the scale, <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON> does _ and makes the show more effective and more unsettling. Her villains are much more vulnerable and everyday `` normal.'' At the end of the musical, when the actors turn and point their fingers at the audience, <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON> makes the point that there may be a little bit of `` Sweeney Todd'' lurking in all of us. What other critics said: <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Rich </PERSON>, The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Times: `` By forcing us to face Mr. <PERSON> Sondheim </PERSON>'s music and the feelings it contains so intensely, Ms. <PERSON> Schulman </PERSON> does n't obliterate the Prince production; she creates an alternative. Such is the depth of Mr. <PERSON> Sondheim </PERSON>'s achievement that ` Sweeney Todd' can support radically different interpretations.'' <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Winer </PERSON>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Newsday: `` The show ... is a fast, raging, beautifully bittersweet and deliciously junky Grand Guignol.'' <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelsen </PERSON>, Daily News: `` ` <PERSON> Todd </PERSON>' is too long at 2 hours and 55 minutes, but its music and performances are worth it.''
