<SECOND>PM-AIDS Costs,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Early AIDS Detection, Treatment Could Cost Billions: Study</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Early detection and treatment of those infected with the AIDS virus may help avert one of the most serious epidemics of our time, but the cost of doing so may push the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> health system into chaos, medical researchers said today. The cost of finding and treating those who carry the virus but are not yet ill could reach $ 5 billion or more a year, with urban areas the hardest hit, researchers reported in today's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` While the economic challenge of early intervention is substantial for hard-hit regions, it can be managed if the federal government takes on greater financial responsibility,'' said the researchers from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Montefiore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and the universities of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Recent advances in the treatment of those infected with the virus but who do not yet have full-fledged cases of AIDS make a compelling case for expanding early treatment, said the researchers, led by <ORGANIZATION> Montefiore </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Arno </PERSON>. Because of new antiviral therapies that slow the disease and drugs that can prevent a common form of pneumonia associated with the disease, early detection may slow the fatal disease's progress, the researchers said. They suggested that policymakers devise a strategy that expands the capabilities of hospital-affiliated out-patient clinics to accommodate better patient monitoring and increased counseling. The authors estimate that the annual cost for a patient with no symptoms would be about $ 854 until drug intervention is needed. Once drugs and increased medical care are needed, a midrange estimate would be about $ 9,600 annually, they said. If treatment were available to half of those infected with the HIV virus today, the cost would be more than $ 4.8 billion, assuming more than 1 million people currently carry the virus but are not yet diagnosed with AIDS. The article also suggested overpricing by drug companies accounts for a large portion of early treatment costs. Drug therapy will account for approximately 80 percent of the cost of early intervention, they said. One company's ability to market a drug without price restraints has led to a quadrupling of its parent company's stock, it said. `` Although drug companies have a legitimate need to recoup their -LRB- research -RRB- investments ... the public expects reasonable prices for life-saving drugs,'' they wrote.
