<HEAD>FCC Chairman Urges Voluntary Code Against `Shock Radio'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> chairman urged the nation's broadcasters Friday to tune out `` shock radio,'' programs that use sexually and racially oriented humor to attract audiences. `` We are not simply recorders, transmitters and antennas,'' <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Sikes </PERSON> told those attending the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION> radio convention. `` We are what we broadcast.'' <PERSON> Sikes </PERSON>, a former owner of several radio stations, said the association should revive its programming code, dropped in the early 1980s as the result of a federal anti-trust lawsuit against provisions regarding commercials. Such standards should be drawn up by the industry, without government pressure, said <PERSON> Sikes </PERSON>, who took over the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> chair in August. The <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> on Aug. 24 said it was taking enforcement action against three stations _ WLUP-AM in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> KSJO-FM </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> WFBQ-FM </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> _ `` which may have broadcast indecent programs in violation of the law.'' The stations were given 30 days to respond to <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> inquiries, which the agency said were based on a review of public complaints. According to <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> transcripts, the material involved sexually oriented humor broadcast during daytime hours. `` I know that people say the commissioners were simply responding to congressional pressures,'' <PERSON> Sikes </PERSON> said. `` But, in that regard, let me say this: You really ought to first read the program material which we cited, and also note that it was being broadcast at a time when children almost certainly were listening.'' NAB President <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Fritts </PERSON> said the organization could not consider a new code unless <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> approves pending legislation granting the broadcast industry an anti-trust exemption for programming content codes.
