<HEAD>Officials Worried About Spies Among Refugees</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Counterintelligence officials said Friday they are worried <LOCATION> Communist </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> may have slipped spies among refugees coming from <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, and they promised to help any spies who turn themselves in. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> has been a playground for spies since the advent of the Cold War, with agents from several <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc countries snooping around for <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> military secrets and sensitive high-tech know-how. Some of the hundreds of spies caught in the past were East Germans who came over to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> either as escapees or as legal emigres. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Frisch </PERSON>, vice president of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s main counterintelligence agency, the <ORGANIZATION> Constitutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, said there may have been agents or would-be agents among the recent flood of East German refugees to the West. `` This is a possibility we must reckon with. It's something we must be alert to,'' said <PERSON> Frisch </PERSON>. He appealed to any East German refugees who have `` obligated themselves'' to East German intelligence to telephone the <ORGANIZATION> Constitutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cologne </LOCATION>. `` We can help them,'' he said. <PERSON> Frisch </PERSON> said that even if a refugee had committed himself to spy for <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, he would not be prosecuted if he had not yet begun his work. Intelligence officials say dramatically reduced East-West tensions have not reduced East bloc espionage. Sixty suspected spies were nabbed in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> last year, compared with 34 the year before. A 69-year-old man was arrested last month for allegedly acting as an East German informer more than 30 years. Some of the world's most famous spy scandals have erupted in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, such as the 1974 exposure of <PERSON> Guenter </PERSON> <PERSON> Guillaume </PERSON>, a close adviser to then-Chancellor <PERSON> Willy </PERSON> <PERSON> Brandt </PERSON>, as an East German agent. The disclosure shocked the nation and resulted in <PERSON> Brandt </PERSON>'s resignation There also have been instances of so-called `` Romeo spies'' coming to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> from the East and building a seemingly innocent life with a respectable job, but at some point romancing government secretaries, exchanging love and companionship for secrets. West German intelligence officials say they have no indications there are spies among the estimated 14,000 East Germans who arrived in the past week but that the possibility can not be excluded. <PERSON> Hans-Gert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lange </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Constitutional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION>, said that sometimes East Germans who ask to leave for the West are first coerced into making deals with East German intelligence. `` Permission to leave would be dependent on making an agreement. If they climb to important positions -LRB- in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> -RRB- where they might be useful, the agreement could be activated,'' he said.
