<HEAD>Industrial Production Rose 0.3 Percent In August</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Industrial production recorded its biggest gain in four months in August, the government said Friday in a report that drew mixed reaction to the 0.3 percent gain. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said the August production rate followed revised increases of 0.1 percent in July and 0.2 percent in June after remaining flat in May. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> originally had reported production rose 0.2 percent in July, but fell 0.1 percent in both May and June. Production was up 0.7 percent in April. `` That's not only stronger than expected, but the revisions were substantial. The economy never really slowed down,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Evans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> consulting firm. However, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> MacReynolds </PERSON>, forecasting director of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, said the gain was only 2.8 percent over August of last year after rising 5.7 percent in 1988. `` Growth in the manufacturing sector has been sluggish throughout 1989, falling farther behind the growth in the services sector,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> credited almost all the August growth to a rebound in production at auto factories and a pickup in coal mining following a strike. `` Excluding motor vehicles, output of both consumer goods and business equipment was sluggish during the summer,'' it said. At the same time, the central bank reported that the operating rate of the nation's factories, mines and utilities remained unchanged at 83.8 percent of capacity in August. The operating rate measures not only output, but also changes in productivity levels. Factory use had declined 0.1 percentage point in June, the central bank said. The rate had hit a 10-year high of 84.3 percent in December 1988 and last January. Last month's operating rate also was unchanged from August 1988. `` Unchanged capacity utilization in August signals the likelihood that inflationary pressures have declined substantially in the last several months,'' <PERSON> MacReynolds </PERSON> said. The closer <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry gets to full operating capacity, the greater difficulty it has producing enough to meet demand, leading to shortages and price increases. Analysts generally consider an operating rate of 85 percent or above as an indication of inflationary pressures. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> has been walking a fine line of keeping interest rates high enough to cool inflationary pressures without slowing growth so much that the economy slides into a recession. Industrial production at manufacturing plants making both durable and non-durable goods rose 0.2 percent last month after remaining flat in July and increasing 0.3 percent in June. Output was up 2.3 percent at mines and oil wells but fell 1 percent at utilities. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> said its industrial production index in August stood at 142.4 percent of its 1977 base, up from 142 percent in July. At the same time, the operating rate rose 0.1 percentage point to 84 percent at manufacturing plants. The rate had peaked at 84.7 percent in January. The rate at factories producing durable goods _ big-ticket items expected to last more than three years _ rose 0.2 percentage point to 82.6 percent. The rate at factories producing non-durable goods fell from 86.4 percent in July to 86.1 percent in August.
</TEXT>
