<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Angolan rebel leader <PERSON> Jonas </PERSON> <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> will visit the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> next month to meet with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials, possibly including President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, official and private sources said Friday. <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON>, who heads the Union for the Total Independence of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- has been invited by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Task </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> on <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and will arrive here Oct. 2, said a source close to his organization. `` A meeting with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is under consideration, but it's quite possible,'' said an administration official who asked not to be named. The official said <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> would brief the administration about the precarious peace talks between his organization and the Marxist government of <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>. He is also expected to discuss the terms of the truce accord and to ask for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support in achieving closer <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> monitoring of the pullout of an estimated 50,000 Cuban troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> and the government agreed on a truce to end their 14-year war at a meeting in <LOCATION> Gbadolite </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> last June, but the cease-fire collapsed soon after and hundreds have died in the ensuing clashes. The agreement has also been endangered by questions about <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON>'s fate. <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> contends <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> agreed to go into temporary exile and integrate his troops into the Angolan military. But <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> denied this and accused the Angolans of lying about the closed-door meeting in <LOCATION> Gbadolite </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has been seeking to bring the sides back to the negotiating table and a meeting has been scheduled for Monday in <LOCATION> Kinshasa </LOCATION>. Assistant Secretary of State <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> this week to help arrange the meeting. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has promised <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> that it will maintain its military and financial support of <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> until a final peace agreement is reached which allows free elections. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, which backs the government in <LOCATION> Luanda </LOCATION>, has also pledged its support until peace is achieved. The Angolan peace talks are a result of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet-sponsored agreement signed last December for the pullout of some 50,000 Cuban troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. The pullout has been conducted according to plan and is expected to be completed on schedule in 1991. <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON>, who once studied in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, last visited here in 1988 and met with former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>.
