<HEAD>Bill Envisions Large-Scale Effort to Make Fish Safe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A House panel began considering a bill Friday that would require health inspection of fish and shellfish, the first effort to establish a comprehensive program to regulate the fishing industry. `` Currently, many consumers are wary about the safety of fish,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Calif </LOCATION>., who introduced the bill `` They have heard many stories about contamination from toxic industrial and agricultural chemicals, medical waste products and red tides.'' The `` Fish and Fish Products Safety Act of 1989'' would require setting safety standards for contaminants for fish and establishing a rigorous and comprehensive inspection system. Officials say it is more difficult to regulate fishing than the meat or poultry industry because there are 300 edible species of fish in vast waters. Contaminants for fish and shellfish include the botulism toxin, salmonella bacteria and the hepatitis-A virus, as well as PCBs and other industrial contaminants. Dr. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, testified before <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on health and the environment that fish consumption increased to 15.4 pounds person in 1987 largely because the food is low in fat. <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> inspects only a quarter of the fish-processing plants each year. He said data from the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> `` indicate that seafood does not cause illness in alarming amounts or diversity.'' However, <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Haas </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit group that deals with food safety issues, disagreed. She offered a <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> study that indicated that the risk of a food poisoning outbreak from eating seafood is 25 times greater from seafood than from beef, and 16 times greater than for either chicken or pork. Dr. <PERSON> Lester </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crawford </PERSON>, administrator of the food safety and inspection service at the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, said that `` building on the existing meat and poultry inspection program structure would provide a faster start up and extensive cost-savings for a fish and seafood inspection program.'' Legislation has been introduced in the past to give the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> authority over seafood inspections, just as it is in charge of meat and poultry inspections. The <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON> bill would make the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> the lead agency. <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON> said in his opening statement Friday that `` the most contentious issue has become one of turf _ where authority over the new fish inspection program should be vested.''
