<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     09-15 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Shuttle,0427</SECOND>
<HEAD>Space Shuttle Crew Ends Rehearsal, Plans Vice Presidential Visit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The crew of space shuttle Atlantis concluded a two-day countdown rehearsal Friday and traveled to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for a meeting with Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. The practice session, intended to mimic the 24 hours leading to an actual launch, went smoothly despite two computer glitches that delayed the end of the countdown, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Malone </PERSON> said. Soon after wrapping up the rehearsal, the five astronauts boarded their T-38 jets for a flight to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. White House officials said <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> planned to meet commander <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> and his crewmates Saturday at breakfast. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> comes from <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s home state of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>. `` Mr. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> expressed a desire to say hello to the crew sometime before we fly,'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> told reporters Thursday. `` I invited him to be a launch guest, but we'll be pretty busy and wo n't be able to visit with him on launch morning.'' The rehearsal ended at 11:10 a.m. EDT, about 10 minutes later than planned, because launch crews needed extra time to investigate two problems in computers monitoring the shuttle's systems. The astronauts and their support crews carried the dress rehearsal to its finish, even though stormy weather near the Kennedy Space Center would have prevented an actual liftoff. Atlantis' liftoff is tentatively scheduled for Oct. 12. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> will not set a firm date until a two-day flight readiness review is completed Oct. 3. The astronauts were aboard Atlantis for the final two hours of the countdown during the dry run. In addition to <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, the crew members are pilot <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> McCully </PERSON> and mission specialists <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON>, <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Chang </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON> <PERSON> Lucid </PERSON>. During the first day of the five-day flight, the astronauts are to dispatch the nuclear-powered <ORGANIZATION> Galileo </ORGANIZATION> spacecraft on the start of a six-year voyage to explore Jupiter and its moons. Anti-nuclear activists have said they will try to block the launch, either by court action or by trespassing at the launch site, because the probe is powered by two generators fueled by plutonium-238. They are afraid an accident during launch would sprinkle hazardous radioactive fallout on communities surrounding the Kennedy Space Center. Similar nuclear generators have provided electrical power on 22 previous <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> space flights, including the six manned Apollo moon missions and the Voyager 2 probe, which recently sent back pictures of the planet <LOCATION> Neptune </LOCATION>. The five astronauts on the mission say they are confident the nuclear generators are safe.
