<HEAD>Teen-agers Impose Justice on Peers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DADE CITY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jury of teen-agers let two boys walk on charges of stealing a bicycle but convicted two others of automobile theft in a courtroom experiment to let young scofflaws be judged by their peers. Circuit Judge <PERSON> Maynard </PERSON> <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> had the final say Thursday and partially disagreed with the verdicts of the six-member jury from <ORGANIZATION> Zephyrhills </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION>. It was the first of semimonthly sessions endorsed by judges, educators and <LOCATION> Pasco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> officials. The jury, volunteers from a class on the law, deliberated about 20 minutes before finding a 14-year-old boy and a 16-year-old boy innocent of stealing the bicycle, but <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> overruled the panel. He explained to the jurors there was enough proof to support a guilty verdict. The judge withheld a finding of guilt, placed the pair on probation and ordered them to pay restitution. The jury contended that the prosecutor, a real one, never tied the boys to the theft and that others were involved but avoided getting hauled into court. `` If they got off with it the others should have, too,'' said juror <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON> <PERSON> Chancery </PERSON>, a senior. In the other case, the jury found two boys guilty of auto theft but innocent of a burglary charge. This time, the judge agreed. `` I thought you were very astute,'' <PERSON> Swanson </PERSON> told the jury. The boys, whose ages were not available, will be punished later this month by the judge. Teacher <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Brendle </PERSON> said the experiment is a lively way for students to learn about the law and also should serve as a deterrent to youngsters who face criminal charges.
