<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The huge store of information in the Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could be made available to libraries and scholars across the country through an improved computer network, the nation's chief librarian said Friday. `` The Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the national library community want to help develop a national research and education network,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Billington </PERSON>, the librarian of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee. `` The major information resources for this nation reside in the Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and other research libraries across the country. These collections have been assembled in many cases with federal, state and local revenues. `` Our citizens have a right to expect that these irreplaceable intellectual resources be made ever more widely available through a national information network,'' he said. <PERSON> Billington </PERSON> testified in favor of a bill sponsored by Sen. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, D-Tenn., which calls for the establishment of national computer-based research network <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> chairs the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> science subcommittee, which held Friday's hearing. `` Books would be stored digitally on magnetic tape, compact discs or on computers,'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said. `` Using a computer, library patrons could access information from the books in the library's collection. `` Thousands of books could be on-line, available at the touch of a button,'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> said, adding that the technology already exists. The Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, with 88 million items, is the largest collection of recorded and printed information ever assembled in a single place, <PERSON> Billington </PERSON> said. One of the question