rs from those business, education, church, student and labor sectors. It excludes the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government. <PERSON> Armando </PERSON> <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON>, director of the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Calif.-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>, said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government was left out because it has underestimated <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s relationship with <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> for too long. However, <ORGANIZATION> IMPACTO </ORGANIZATION> realizes that the growing Hispanic population in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is an issue that has to be addressed, <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON> said. About 20 million Hispanics live in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> today, 62 percent of them born there, <PERSON> Navarro </PERSON> said. He said projections indicate half of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s residents by 2030 will be Hispanic. Members of the 4-year-old coalition met with <PERSON> Salinas </PERSON> last year and the president promised to listen to their proposal after he was elected.
