<FIRST>u i AM-WarrenRemembered Bjt   09-15 0940</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warren Remembered, Bjt,0972</SECOND>
<HEAD>Robert Penn Warren: A Sense of Adventure</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Herzfelder </PERSON>, now the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s News Editor for <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, has known <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Penn </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> since 1972, when he studied under him at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The cancer that would kill him was already at work. He could n't lift weights or walk young men and women into breathlessness any more. But <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Penn </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> refused to be a sick man; he did n't want to talk about that. He was the first poet laureate of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and he had a speech to write. I drove him and his wife, <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON>, from his summer home in <LOCATION> Stratton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vt. </LOCATION>, to a hospital in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. Even about that there was a sense of adventure. Would we get lost? Stuck in a snowbank? There could be no such thing as disaster. He told me his daughter <PERSON> Rosanna </PERSON> had been born at home during a snowstorm, no doctors could get to the house. That was an adventure too. But perhaps only in retrospect. We discussed poetry, the news, war and rock music. You could n't be depressed around him It seemed silly. Mr. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> _ I never called him anything else, though his nickname was ` Red,' for the red hair of his youth _ was generous enough to let me think of him as a friend. I took the last class he taught at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>, a writing course given in the fall of 1972. He was 67 then, the author of `` All The King's Men. What more could he do, I thought. That was a book from the 1940s. At first it was awful. He was an old-fashioned teacher. He did n't like fools, and did n't seem to believe in give-and-take in the classroom Sometimes he looked like a crocodile. Then he read <PERSON> Rudyard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kipling </PERSON>'s story `` The Man Who Would Be King'' to the class. It was amazing that his high-pitched <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> accent _ he never lost it despite years in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> _ could recreate the dry mountains of northern <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. He invited the class to his house for dinner, introduced us to leading literary lights _ `` This is <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Cheever </PERSON>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hersey </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellison </PERSON>.'' I was drinking bourbon because I did n't want to seem like a wimp. Nervous, I emptied my glass quickly. `` You look like you need a DRINK,'' he said, refilling my glass. After about six of those I went downstairs and took a nap on the dining room floor. That's where I was when the first guests walked in for supper. He liked that. He came from a generation that thought it romantic to drink to oblivion daily. Though he cut down in later years, I stayed up with him a couple of times. What I could n't do was get up the next morning, lift weights and take a two-mile walk. Then it was time to work. Work. People who telephoned him in the morning got an awful shock. He'd answer, but you were interrupting work. He did n't much like telephones anyway. He once wrote a poem called `` Little Black Heart of the Telephone.'' At the time I did n't understand why that might be important. I did n't understand how easy it was to lose time, how hard it is to concentrate and get more than three things done in a day. How hard it was for a man to keep producing after winning two Pulitzer Prizes. He `` retired'' from <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION>, then he won his third Pulitzer. He did n't particularly need it. What he needed was the work. Mr. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> taught me a lot of things, few of them in class. He taught by example, by his energy, by his love of truth and beauty, by his sense of adventure. He and his wife taught me and many others that it's possible for two competitive people to love each other and have a happy marriage. Mrs. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> writes under the name <PERSON> Eleanor </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>. Their tennis court is a memorial to the National Book Award _ it was built with her prize money. None of those prizes stopped them from wearing funny hats on New Year's Eve. There is a final memory, my favorite. He told me later he'd thought I was his stupidest student because I never talked in class Finally he called me in for a private conference. Somehow I mentioned that I had just read <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> Tennyson </PERSON>'s poem `` Ulysses'' for the first time. The last line has become a cliche, but I thought it was stunning when read as the climax to a great poem. He almost leaped out of his chair and yelped, `` It's a MAGNIFICENT poem.'' I started reciting the first lines planning to make some learned comment, or rather some comment that would make me seem learned. Instead, he simply joined me. Together we recited the whole poem. I could not believe I was remembering it all, but it seemed easy. The poem describes <PERSON> Ulysses </PERSON>' years after the Trojan wars and his 10-year homeward Odyssey, old but still determined to push on to new adventure in spite of all risk, trouble or weakness. I did n't realize how much that might have meant to Mr. <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> until just now. This is how it ends:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Though much is taken, much abides; and though We are not now that strength which in old days Moved earth and heaven; that which we are, we are; One equal temper of heroic hearts, Made weak by time and fate, but strong in will To strive, to seek, to find, and not to yield.
</TEXT>
