<HEAD>Battle Launched to Against Livestock Pests</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An all-out war against screwworms has been launched in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> to help prevent the livestock pests from migrating to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Glosser </PERSON>, administrator of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Animal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said about 20 screwworm larvae were found Sept. 5 near <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Juan </LOCATION> on a horse that had been shipped from <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>. Beginning Friday, he said, about 800,000 sexually sterilized screwworm flies will be released twice a week for six weeks in a five-mile radius around the airport and the quarantine station. The technique floods the suspected area with sterile male flies. If a female mates with one, her eggs will not hatch, thus ending the life cycle. Normally, the eggs are laid in open sores or wounds of warm-blooded animals, hatching out into worms that feed on the living flesh. <PERSON> Glosser </PERSON> said the adult screwworm fly is about twice the size of a house fly, with orange eyes and a bluish-green body with three dark stripes along the back. Screwworm larvae are creamy white and grow to about half an inch in length after five to seven days of feeding. Screwworms were eradicated in <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION> in 1975. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was declared free of the pests in 1966, although small infestations have occurred since then, mostly along the U.S.-Mexico border.
