<HEAD>Farm Bureau Chief Favors Capital Gains Tax Cut</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Capital Gains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee's vote to reinstate preferential capital gains tax rates will help `` mom-and-pop type'' farmers, not just rich people, a national farm leader said Friday. <PERSON> Dean </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleckner </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, said there are family farmers all over the country who have owned land for many years and now want to sell out and retire. But because of inflation, land values have increased so much that many can not afford to retire after paying high capital gains taxes on the sales. `` We're talking about mom-and-pop type of agriculture here,'' <PERSON> Kleckner </PERSON> said in a statement. `` We're not talking about wealthy farmers.'' <PERSON> Kleckner </PERSON> added that `` it's kind of a populist idea that capital gains are only for wealthy people. It's going to be extremely helpful for all of agriculture, and most of agriculture is not in the extremely wealthy class.'' The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> voted 19-17 on Thursday to cut the tax.
