<HEAD>Inouye Calls For Indians To Settle $50 Million Dispute Themselves</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Indian Affairs said Friday he wants the <ORGANIZATION> Seminole </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indians </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> to settle a $ 50 million dispute themselves instead of asking <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to handle it. `` In most cases, decisions made in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> for Indians are the worst solutions,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Hawaii </LOCATION>. `` Decisions should be made in Indian country.'' His comments came during a hearing on legislation that would divide money awarded the tribe in 1976 for <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> lands taken when most of the tribe was relocated by the government to <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> in the 1823 `` Trail of Tears.'' The award _ $ 16 million _ has been held by the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> for 23 years because the members of the tribe, many of whom still live in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, have not agreed on how it should be divided. It has accumulated substantial interest, and it is estimated to reach $ 50 million by the end of this year. Legislation sponsored by <PERSON> Oklahoma </PERSON> <PERSON> Sens </PERSON>. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Boren </PERSON>, a Democrat, and <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Nickles </PERSON>, Republican, would give 75 percent of the money to the <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seminoles </LOCATION> and 25 percent to the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seminoles </ORGANIZATION>, the <LOCATION> Miccosukee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tribe </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and the unaffiliated Seminole Indians of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Nickles </PERSON> said the split is fair because it's based on population figures that counted 2,146 Seminoles in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and 700 in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. He also said the <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> tribe is poorer than the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> one. `` Not only did hundreds of Seminoles die during the forced march from <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> to <ORGANIZATION> Indian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Territory </ORGANIZATION>, but lands initially given to the tribe as a reservation were later taken from them as <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> became a state,'' said <PERSON> Nickles </PERSON>. `` Today the Seminole Nation -LRB- in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> -RRB- has a total of only 380 acres of tribally owned land,'' he said. On the other hand, he said, the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> tribe `` is flourishing economically with a reservation land base of approximately 80,000 acres.'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Billie </PERSON>, tribal council chairman for the <ORGANIZATION> Seminoles </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> who want a 50-50 split, told the committee he thought the two sides could come to some agreement if they had 30 more days. `` While we in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> have a sharp disagreement with our <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> brethren over the division of the claims commission's award, we have not lost sight of the fact that we are all one people,'' <PERSON> Billie </PERSON> said. `` As a result of recent informal preliminary discussions we have had with some of our <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> brethren, we believe that it still may be possible in a relatively short time ... to have agreement reached by the two groups.'' `` I would prefer negotiations,'' said <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>. He said sovereign nations, as Indian tribes are viewed, should be able to negotiate.
