<SECOND>AM-Drunken Drivers,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governor Signs Bill Lowering Legal Drinking Limit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUG WILLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> predicted lives will be saved by legislation he signed Friday to lower <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s blood-alcohol standard for drunken drivers `` We are seeing a reduction in the number of traffic fatalities caused by drunken drivers,'' he told reporters and law enforcement officers gathered in his office for the bill signing. `` On the other hand, we still have a far greater number of such fatalities than we should have in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. This will make it possible for law enforcement to obtain greater numbers of convictions,'' the Republican governor said. <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> said 2,239 people died last year as a result of drunken drivers on <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> highways. The law, effective Jan. 1, lowers the blood-alcohol level at which a person is presumed too drunk to drive from 0.10 percent to 0.08 percent. Current law allows for prosecution when a driver's blood-alcohol level is below 0.10 percent if there is other evidence the driver was too intoxicated to drive safely Convictions are rare, however. The new law still allows for prosecutions at levels below 0.08 percent if other evidence warrants it. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> supports a 0.05 percent level. A variety of factors, including weight, affect the amount of alcohol a person can consume before getting drunk. The average person can consume about three glasses of beer or comparable amounts of other alcoholic beverages in an hour before reaching the 0.08 percent level. Drunken drivers should beware of the lowered standard, <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> said. `` This is a very strong signal and message to individuals who do drink and do drive that it is more likely that they will wind up being convicted of drunken driving ...,'' he said.
