<HEAD>House Panel Asks Justice Department to Probe FAA Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel charged Friday that <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials lied under oath about payroll records prepared during the 1981 controllers' strike and in some instances doctored time sheets to cheat the controllers. The committee asked the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to investigate. Faced with shoddy documents to justify the firings before the <ORGANIZATION> Merit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> for three months created attendance records to bolster their cases, lawmakers concluded. The report by the <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on investigations and oversight capped a three-year probe that included private hearings and documents subpoenaed from the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Route </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Aurora </LOCATION>, Ill. The panel said it was willing to send its evidence to the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and sent a letter to Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> urging an investigation into possible criminal misconduct. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Leyden </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, declined comment except to say, `` The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> has receieved the report and will review it.'' The subcommittee said it was not judging the merits of the 450 firings in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, which were among 11,500 nationwide ordered Aug. 5, 1981, by then-President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, two days after members of the <ORGANIZATION> Professional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Controllers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> struck. Rather, the subcommittee said it was concerned with the actions of <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials while they were defending the firings in front of the board that considers appeals from dismissed federal employees. For example, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials corrected some attendance records to bring them up to date, but altered others, in some instances recording a controller who was on leave at the time of the strike as being absent without leave, to cheat the controllers, the subcommittee said. The panel's report said the strike produced `` traumatic and confusing times'' at the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> center. Supervisors had to handle other jobs, `` and this situation severely affected the condition of the center's attendance records,'' the report said. On Aug. 13, 1981, 10 days after the strike began and a month before the controllers were told formally they had been fired, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, evaluations officer at the center, began to process personnel files in anticipation that appeals would be filed with the appeals board, the subcommittee said. To justify the firings, <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials decided to present attendance records showing that the controllers had failed to report to work during the strike. Between Sept. 14 and Oct. 1, these records were sent to the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s Great Lakes regional office in <LOCATION> Des </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plaines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, but officials there found so many clerical errors that employees in <LOCATION> Aurora </LOCATION> had to produce a second set of attendance records, the subcommittee said <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> officials subsequently assured the merit board that the records were the ones that had been used by <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON>, the chief of the <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> center and the official who ordered the firings. The subcommittee concluded, however, that the assurance was `` a certification that we now know to be false.'' `` These documents, in many cases, either did not exist at the time of the controller dismissals or were riddled with errors,'' the subcommittee said. `` A plan was instituted whereby records were created where none existed and amended where there were errors.'' The subcommittee said it was not able to determine who had ordered the second set of records. The subcommittee's report also concluded that <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shewfelt </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s regional manager for labor relations at the time, `` knew of the problems of consistency and accuracy in the records that led to the second shipment.'' Shewfelt, who still works for the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> office, did not return phone messages requesting comment. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> is retired and could not be found for comment. <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON>, now supervisor of training at the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Route </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Fremont </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, said he had not seen the report and declined to comment.
