 The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Friday that it had joined a whistleblower's lawsuit charging that <ORGANIZATION> Fairchild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> defrauded the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> by selling the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> faulty jet fighter equipment. The department said it had taken over the lawsuit filed by <PERSON> Neil </PERSON> <PERSON> Aliksanian </PERSON>, who was a program manager for Fairchild until leaving the company in 1987. The government's complaint amending the original allegations made by <PERSON> Aliksanian </PERSON> was unsealed Thursday by a federal judge in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Schiffer </PERSON>, acting head of the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s civil division, said in a statement that the government is claiming more than $ 1 million in civil penalties for filing false claims. The government contends that <ORGANIZATION> Fairchild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a division of the <LOCATION> Chantilly </LOCATION>, Va.-based defense company, sold the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> defective fuel-tank equipment for jet fighters. <PERSON> Aliksanian </PERSON>'s original lawsuit was filed under the False Claims Act, a Civil War-era law that allows private citizens to sue on behalf of the government. His complaint was kept under court seal until last month. The government's amended complaint was filed under seal in June.
