<HEAD>Afghan Troops Welcome Trucks with Garlands, Slaughtered Sheep</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MACFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANDAHAR, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Children clapped, the governor was showered with cloth garlands and a sheep was slaughtered in the middle of the road Friday as the military welcomed about 200 vehicles from a supply convoy that began rolling last month. The anti-Marxist rebels welcomed the convoy in their own way. Two rockets slammed down about 250 feet from where the provincial governor, Gen. <PERSON> Noor </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Haq </PERSON> <PERSON> Ulumi </PERSON>, was talking to reporters as trucks and tanks rumbled past. No injuries were reported. <PERSON> Ulumi </PERSON> said almost 1,000 trucks had snaked their way across almost 780 miles of the barren south before arriving in this southeastern provincial capital this week. In <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, sources from the mujahedeen _ or Islamic holy warriors, the Afghan rebels based in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> _ and diplomatic sources said the rebels knocked out 80 vehicles and slowed the convoy's forward progress to a snail's pace. The sources spoke on condition of anonymity. <PERSON> Ulumi </PERSON> said the convoy lost three trucks in a collision and one tank to a land mine. He said it had not suffered any mujahedeen attacks after leaving <PERSON> Grishik </PERSON>, 60 miles west of <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION>. Earlier, government officials said rebel forces attacked the convoy at least three times and rebel rocket attacks forced it to halt between <LOCATION> Grishik </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION>. Initial government reports also said 1,300 vehicles were in the convoy. The rockets Friday scattered the welcoming crowd that had been throwing cloth flowers threaded onto metal rings. The throat of the lone sacrificial sheep was cut with a dull knife in front of the lead vehicle, and tires left gory imprints on the road. The trucks rumbling through the outskirts of <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION> Friday were the second batch to reach the city. <PERSON> Ulumi </PERSON> said with more expected each day. He said the convoy was carrying ammunition and food and included 500 military trucks, 300 civilian trucks and a brigade of armored vehicles. He would not say how many. There were no civilian trucks and no food in the carefully orchestrated welcoming ceremony. The military trucks were flanked by 32 tanks. Most were stacked with ammunition boxes and caked with dirt. Some were empty with spanking clean cabs. <PERSON> Ulumi </PERSON> said they were unloaded earlier at a nearby garrison. Many trucks seemed new. Government officials have said the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> recently delivered more than 1,000 trucks to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ulumi </PERSON> said the ammunition should last troops in the area a year, depending on the extent of fighting. `` If there is no war, the supplies will last 10 years, if there is a war, one year,'' he said. It is the first such convoy since February, when Soviet troops withdrew from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> nine years after intervening to prop up the Marxist government. The U.S.-backed mujahedeen are still fighting the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> government. The mujahedeen have not captured a major city despite repeated attempts. The convoy was seen as a warning to the mujahedeen that their acknowledged primacy in rural areas could be weakened. Officials in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> were always upbeat about the trucks' progress, but repeated claims that the convoy was on the outskirts of <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION> were constantly revised. Ulumi would not say when the trucks had pulled out of <LOCATION> Torghundi </LOCATION>, on the northern border with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Government sources in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> have said the departure date was Aug. 18. <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION> lies 350 miles to the northwest of <LOCATION> Torghundi </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ulumi </PERSON> claimed progress toward <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION> was slow because the trucks were used to supply a new set of border posts near <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Speaking through an interpreter, he said the posts should make it harder for the mujahedeen to use clansdestine routes through the <LOCATION> Registan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Desert </LOCATION> to get into <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. Supplies muust be brought into <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> during the summer because winter rain and snow make the roads impassable. Guerrillas have tried since October 1987 to capture <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION> and heavy fighting has left much of the city in ruins. <PERSON> Ulumi </PERSON> said two weeks ago that 70 percent of the buildings in the city were completely destroyed. <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION> is 70 miles from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and about 270 miles south of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, the Afghan capital. It was <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s second largest city with about 300,000 people before the civil war began nearly 11 years ago. Govertment officials said the population fell to about 25,000 when bombardment was at its heaviest, but later talked of 200,000 now living in <LOCATION> Kandahar </LOCATION>.
