CATION> Fredericton </LOCATION>, and police said <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> was arrested while trying to extend the rental agreement. The four men were also carrying maps of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION> and neighboring <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. Police said several locations were highlighted on the maps but refused to say what they were. The suspected cocaine traffickers, <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Galindo-Escobar </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fernando </PERSON> <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Mendoza-Jaramillo </PERSON>, both 36, were arrested in April after police made <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s largest cocaine seizure. They found about 1,100 pounds of the drug inside the nose of an airplane at a makeshift airstrip outside <LOCATION> Fredericton </LOCATION>. At Thursday's hearing, the two were ordered held for trial next month on charges of importing cocaine. Authorities used dozens of rifle-toting officers for heavy security at the hearing because of worries prompted by the arrests.
