<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Salvadoran government and leftist rebels agreed Friday to meet monthly to try to negotiate an end to their 10-year-old civil war that has claimed 70,000 lives. Crowds marched through the streets of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> cheering the <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> agreements, and right-wing President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> said he was encouraged. Leaders of the rebel <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> said their hope was for peace in 1990. The rebels and the government agreed to meet next in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jose </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rican </LOCATION> capital, on Oct. 16-17 and at 30-day intervals thereafter. They agreed that two representatives from the <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> will mediate the talks and that they will also invite the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> to send observers. The <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> government initially opposed church mediation or outside observers. It had also proposed meeting the Front _ known by its Spanish initials <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION> _ every two months instead of at 30-day intervals. The pact, reached after two days of intensive talks, also stipulates that neither side can unilaterally withdraw from the negotiations and that each delegation will have authority to reach binding accords. `` The <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION> hopes there will be a Christmas and New Year in peace in our country and that 1990 will be the year of the war's final end,'' rebel leader <PERSON> Shafick </PERSON> <PERSON> Handal </PERSON> said at a joint news conference after the accord was signed. `` The blood that has been spilled in the longest and most costly conflict on the continent, all this blood that has been spilled, deserves this.'' <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> called the agreement `` important'' but cautioned, `` while welcoming the dialogue process, we do n't want to create false expectations.'' `` We want to reiterate that our attitude is one of openness and flexibility within our constitutional framework ... We know the road ahead is difficult and complex,'' he told an Independence Day rally in the Salvadoran capital. The <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> accord was announced on Central American Independence Day _ the 168th anniversary of the independence of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> in 1821. `` We will possibly confront obstacles. But we trust in God and in the good will of the two sides, and we will overcome the difficulties,'' <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Handal </PERSON> and fellow guerrilla commander <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Villalobos </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION> proposed the talks because of pressure inside and outside their country for peace. They also said they feared the rightist government would become a `` facist dictatorship'' unless checked by the kind of democracy peace could bring. Most of the war's victims have been civilians. Human rights groups and international organizations say many were killed by right-wing death squads linked to the military and <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>'s party _ links the party denies. The <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> talks were the first in two years between government and rebels; they were also the first meeting between the rebels and <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>'s administration. The rebels have already laid out their peace proposal. The government is to present its proposal in October. The <ORGANIZATION> FMLN </ORGANIZATION> offered to transform itself from a rebel army into a legal political party in exchange for sweeping social and political reforms. The reforms would erode the power of the military and of <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>'s party, which now holds controls the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. The rebels demand that the military be purged of human rights violators and reduced in size; that the date of the 1991 legislative and municipal elections be advanced; and that a new high court be appointed. In return, the rebels say they will become a legitimate political party and run candidates in elections _ something they have refused to do. They dropped demands for power-sharing and for merging the rebel and government armies and couched their plan in language far milder than any previous proposal. The proposal asks the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to end military aid to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and channel the money instead into <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON>'s economic development. To prevent a rebel victory, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has given about $ 3.5 billion in military and economic aid to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> this decade _ making it <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s biggest single recipient of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> assistance.
