<HEAD>Warren Remembered as Man of the South, the World</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 10th graf, `Others were ..., with comment
from Librarian of Congress.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Obit-Warren, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY SCHWARTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Penn </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> was remembered Friday as a son of the South who became a citizen of the world, as a brilliant poet, fiction writer, teacher and critic _ and as a nice man. `` He was reticent, ironic, reserved and perfectly charming, and I loved and respected him quite apart from his work,'' said poet <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nemerov </PERSON>, who owns a copy of the first edition of <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>'s first book `` He had such vigor and such love of life. He was such wonderful company _ he was the soul of hilarity,'' said novelist <PERSON> Eudora </PERSON> <PERSON> Welty </PERSON>, whose first work was published in the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Review </ORGANIZATION> when <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> was editor in the 1930s. `` He was a good friend to writers _ constantly generous and giving.'' `` Red'' <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> died Friday at his summer home in <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> after battling cancer for three years. In a literary career that spanned nearly 60 years, he wrote dozens of books and made hundreds of friends. Many were colleagues. <PERSON> Cleanth </PERSON> <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON> developed the `` New Criticism'' with <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, concentrating on the text of literature, not the authors' lives. `` He was one of our truly all-around men who made great contributions in all fields. He was a great poet, fine teacher and did something to revolutionize the modes of teaching literature,'' said <PERSON> Brooks </PERSON>. Others were students. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Axthelm </PERSON>, the writer and TV commentator and a student of <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>'s at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> in the mid-60s, recalled sitting in his office over morning coffee to discuss comic scenes by novelist <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Faulkner </PERSON>. `` I treasure the memory,'' he said. `` When people ask me what the best thing about going to <LOCATION> Yale </LOCATION> was, I always say <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Penn </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>. `` To listen to this man of the South talk about the great southern writer was just an unbelievable privilege. I really did love this man.'' Others were officials of institutions with which he was affiliated. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Billington </PERSON>, Librarian of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>'s `` years at the Library of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> as consultant in poetry and more recently as the nation's first poet laureate consultant in poetry, were marked by extraordinary excellence of achievement. ... His legacy promises to be with Americans for generations to come.'' <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> was `` a wonderfully warm and generous man who is fondly remembered by his former students and colleagues,'' said <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyatt </PERSON>, chancellor of <ORGANIZATION> Vanderbilt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, which <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> attended as an undergraduate and where he joined two important literary movements _ the Fugitives and the Agrarians. The Fugitives -LRB- named after a literary magazine -RRB- argued the importance of a Southern literary identity; the Agrarians warned against the dangers of industrialization, and it was in that connection that <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> wrote an essay defending segregation. He came to repudiate that stance. `` This was in 1930. He just felt that was then, this was now,'' said <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON>, a professor of English at <ORGANIZATION> Vanderbilt </ORGANIZATION> who had known <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> since the late 1940s. `` I think he is going to be read 100 years from now. ` All the King's Men' is already a classic _ generations have read that book,'' <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSO