<HEAD>Racism in Film Detrimental to Whites and Blacks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From Tarzan to <PERSON> Indiana </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, racism in the movies has created false notions and negative images of African-Americans held by both white and black people, two veteran black actors said Friday. `` The dominant culture puts out so much misinformation in a relentless fashion that you are programmed against yourself,'' said <PERSON> Bernie </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>, recalling that as a child he rooted for <PERSON> Tarzan </PERSON> to win against the Africans. `` I did not want to be one of the Africans yet I am an African. I would reject myself ... In the land of ooga-booga, I wanted no part of it,'' <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>, who has appeared in 25 movies and on television, took part in a seminar with <PERSON> Madge </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON> <PERSON> Madge </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON>, late of television's `` Trapper <PERSON> John </PERSON>.'' In making their remarks during a seminar at the Congressional Black Caucus weekend, the two also urged listeners to write in to producers when they are pleased or displeased; refuse to see films or rent videos that do not have black people in significant roles; and form collectives to act on both ideas. `` I never see a Woody <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> film,'' <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON> said about the filmmaker who is acclaimed for filming slices of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> life yet whose few black characters frequently are butlers and maids. `` I feel better when I do n't subscribe to the images that deny my very existence.'' The two agreed that: loving black couples are rarely shown; dashing black men are never the heros; black people are thought to have lips that are too large thus few if any kissing scenes are ever filmed. Also, <PERSON> Tarzan </PERSON>'s successor, <PERSON> Indiana </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, also was in films that `` speak to the evilness'' of the cultures of people of color and those dark people's `` lack of ableness,'' <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said. He added that `` what is born out of misinformation is misperception and what is born of misperception is misunderstanding.'' That has lead to, among other things, black people rejecting their culture by straigtening their hair to be more like white people, <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said. `` As long as you reject yourself, you will never feel of any consequence,'' <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said. And added <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON>, the world only knows about black people what is exported on film, leading to Japanese prime ministers being able to make disparaging remarks about the intelligence of blacks and Latinos. When she was growing up in <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON> said, black people in films were always worthless, shiftless bums or gangsters. Fortunately, she said, she and members of her family traveled to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` and so we knew better.'' Recently <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON> said she was insulted by some black producers who were thinking of casting her. But one of them told her `` he thought I was too polished, too cultured, could I ` get down''' or act in a more stereotypical black manner, <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON> said. `` That floored me and made me want to leave the business,'' she said to the overflow crowd in a <ORGANIZATION> Congressional </ORGANIZATION> hearing room on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. `` That's what I expected from the other side.'' But one of the worst incidents occurred when she went to a producer with a project by and about black people. After presenting all of her arguments for something she thought black people would flock to see, <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON> said the producer told her: `` It does n't matter what we put out there. Anything we put out there they'll go see.'' Too true, the two actors said. <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>, using conservative figures, said that if 20 million blacks saw two movies a month at $ 3 a ticket, that would equal $ 120 million a month and more than $ 1 billion a year. `` So if you think you are inconsequential, stop it,'' <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> said. A visiting black actor from <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> was taken aback by the discussion. `` You've kind of blown me away. We guys thought you were doing so well,'' <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Bovell </PERSON> said to much laughter during the question and answer portion of the program. Afterward, he said black Britons were aware of <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> X </PERSON>, Dr. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Luther </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and also, as seen through the movies, that life in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> was good. `` It was presumed to be the same for blacks,'' <PERSON> Bovell </PERSON> said. `` This has been brilliant for me.''
