cleanup program; picks up 7th graf, `State officials ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As workers who labored to remove the scars of the Exxon Valdez disaster left this port town on Friday, the state announced its own $ 21 million cleanup plan for the winter. Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said the winter program will include cleaning shorelines, researching and developing cleanup technology that can be used next spring, and protecting fish hatcheries and untainted, environmentally sensitive areas. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> officials have pronounced 1,100 miles of oil-smeared shoreline `` environmentally stable,'' saying their 25-week effort to remove gross contamination from shorelines in Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> was a job well done. <PERSON> Otto </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, general manager of <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s Valdez operations, said that while oil remained in some areas, it was not enough to harm wildlife. `` What you've seen is a coastline almost free of oil,'' <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> said at a Valdez news conference. `` You're seeing the steady recovery of Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>.'' Officials at <ORGANIZATION> VECO </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the primary contractor for <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> in the cleanup, defended their work at a news conference on Friday. <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartley </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> VECO </ORGANIZATION>'s general manager, said the removal of oil from beaches was `` Herculean accomplishment.'' `` That does not mean you can not find oil on the beaches. You can find oil if you look for it,'' <PERSON> Hartley </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> was conciliatory toward <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> as he announced the state cleanup. `` I think Exxon has made a good-faith efort to clean up the beaches,'' the governor said. `` I'm not going to fault <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> because they made some mistakes. Frankly, some of the things the state has done were mistakes.'' The state should have known more about dealing with a spill, he said. `` At least we should have known no one else knew how to do it,'' <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said. The state work will be funded with an oil tax the <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> passed this year, and reimbursment will be sought from <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>, the governor said. State officials agreed some shorelines were cleaner because of <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s efforts. But they disputed the company's rosey portrayal of an environmental rebound from nearly 11 million gallons of spilled crude. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelso </PERSON>, the state's environmental commissioner, toured shorelines on two islands south of <LOCATION> Valdez </LOCATION> on Thursday and said he was not pleased with what he saw. `` This beach is not environmentally stable,'' he said as he poked a stick into thickly oiled rocks on <LOCATION> Knight </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>. The Knight Island shoreline was one of the last treated by cleanup crews. The air still was thick with the pungent smell of a chemical fertilizer recently sprayed on the rocks. The fertilizer is supposed to stimulate microorganisms to break down the oil faster than they would normally. <PERSON> Kelso </PERSON>, who had visited the same beach two weeks ago, said the process has shown signs of success. In other spots, however, it appeared the cleanup was rushed to meet <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s self-imposed cleanup deadline, <PERSON> Kelso </PERSON> said. The commissioner said the state is asking <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> to do more research in the coming months to determine the chemicals' possible side effects and whether the process does much more than remove surface oil. Exxon officials said that while the summer cleanup is over, the company will continue to monitor th