<HEAD>You May Know More Than You Know About Inflation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Consumers seem to understand a lot more about inflation than they've been given credit for. Their actions prove it. Unlike the behavior of the 1970s, when the mere mention of the word sent people running to the store to buy things before prices rose _ thus assuring that prices would rise _ today's consumer remains calm. It's a good thing too, because the noise made by inflation alarmists in recent months recalls World War II days, when air raid sirens sent people scurrying to cellars before the bombs fell. Throughout this year the inflation alarmists have screamed warnings every time the government released another monthly report on prices. And they're ready to do it again today, the scheduled release date for August producer prices. Unlike the situation in the 1970s, however, people are n't rushing to buy. They're taking their time instead, forcing automakers into granting discounts. And they're avoiding items on which prices have risen sharply. This avoidance behavior is n't much publicized, but it is very real. People are indeed switching from inflated items to what they consider better buys, and you can demonstrate it from the numbers. There are many measures of inflation, the most popular being the consumer price index. The CPI is based on prices of a `` basket'' of goods and services. Items in that basket were chosen in 1982, based on existing shopping patterns. Another measurement is called the Gross National Product implicit price deflator. It measures not just prices, but changes in spending patterns too. The items in the basket vary in keeping with changes in shopping behavior. Since 1982, the implicit price deflator has averaged 0.4 percent per year less than the fixed basket index. The difference is significant, and it can mean only one thing: Consumers have been avoiding inflated items. Why this should be so is n't as clear as the fact that it is happening. It could be in reaction to the foolishness of the 1970s. It could reflect greater competition and more goods in the marketplace because of imports. Education might be play a role. Instinct, too. Confidence in government? Maybe. One of the likely possibilities is that consumers have been forced into selectivity because workers' earnings have n't been growing explosively, as they did in some periods of the 1970s. Squeeze inflation from the numbers, in fact, and you can see that average hourly earnings are no higher than a decade ago. Whatever the reason, the results are clear. Although shoppers may have little flexibility in deciding what items to buy, they have been exercising choice where they can. Otherwise, the statistical pattern would n't be so clear. This change wo n't silence the alarmists. Unable to break the bad habit, they will still scream their warnings. You might recall that in the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> administration they screamed all the way down into the pit of recession. The big difference between now and the 1970s, however, is that their audience is more critical and informed. Consumers are n't being panicked into buying. Instead, they're remaining cool and selective.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Fri, Sept 15</NOTE>
</DOC>
