<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 17</HEAD>
<HEAD>The South Dissected, Hangups and All</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: This stands for the regular column by Walter R. Mears, who is
vacationing.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE FEINSILBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It says something about the book put out by <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON> and <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> that the major complaint from readers is that it is too heavy to read in bed. Most people do n't take an encylcopedia to bed It says something, too, about the eight-pound, three-ounce Encyclopedia of Southern Culture that not many people except for the citizens of <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, have found much that was left out. <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> complains because it did n't get an entry of its own, making it appear, perhaps, less Southern than <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION>. This massive and ambitious $ 50, 1,600-page compendium of `` the cultural landscape of the South'' _ exploring everything from <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Cash </PERSON> to <ORGANIZATION> Moon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pies </ORGANIZATION> _ was published this summer. Even before it came out, the <ORGANIZATION> Fort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Worth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star-Telegram </ORGANIZATION> carried a piece offering a carload of mint juleps if the book would just include <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>. `` It was a very attractive offer,'' says <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON>, son of a soybean farmer, now director of the Center for the Study of Southern Culture at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mississippi </ORGANIZATION>, but in defining what constitutes Dixie `` we had to draw the line somewhere and we basically drew it between <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>.'' As for the rest of the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> and its institutions, folkways, foods, burdens, icons, topics, attitudes, crops and hangups, `` to my knowledge, there have been no real omissions,'' says <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON>. Which says a lot. Edited jointly by <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON>, a folklorist, and <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, a historian, and 10 years in the works -LRB- it was supposed to have taken four -RRB-, the encyclopedia has 800 contributors, including novelists, theologians, lawyers, psychologists, historians, sociologists. They're specialists on everything from the role violence, race and religion have played on the psyche of the South to the history of the Goo Goo Cluster -LRB- `` the South's favorite candy,'' it got its name, legend says, from the first utterance of the infant son of its creator, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, in 1912 -RRB-. The encyclopedia offers <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s distinction between a good old boy and a redneck. The former rides around in a pickup drinking beer and puts his empties in a sack; the latter rides around in a pickup drinking beer and tossing his empties out the window. <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON> says the criticism he's heard most often from readers concerned the book's size, but some critics have complained about imbalance. Reviewer <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Yardley </PERSON> felt there was too much <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Aaron </PERSON>, too little <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mays </PERSON>, too much <PERSON> Vivian </PERSON> <PERSON> Leigh </PERSON>, not enough <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> <PERSON> Gable </PERSON>. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Egerton </PERSON>, author of `` Southern Food: At Home, On the <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION>, In History,'' complained he could n't find entries on <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Earl </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION>, Happy Chandler, <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> McMurtry </PERSON> or <PERSON> Minnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Pearl </PERSON> and not enough on Southern politics and rivers. Never mind. The book still swarms with the stuff that makes the South distinctive. The flavor is conveyed by just a smattering from the A, B and C entries in the index: _ A: Air conditioning -LRB- `` Ask any southerner over 30 years of age to explain why the South has changed in recent decades, and he may begin with the civil rights movement or industrialization But sooner or later he will come around to the subject of air conditioning.'' -RRB-. The <PERSON> Andy </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffith </PERSON> Show. Armadillos -LRB- come out at night, live on insects and worms, voted in 1971 by the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> student </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> senate </ORGANIZATION> to replace the longhorn as the school symbol, but never acted upon -RRB-. _ B: Barbecue -LRB- `` three topics upon which Southerners never agree are religion, politics and barbecue'' -RRB- The Beverly Hillbillies. The Bible Belt. The Blues. The <PERSON> Boll </PERSON> <PERSON> Weevil </PERSON> -LRB- `` During the initial infestation many communities exclusively dependent on cotton underwent boll weevil panics or depressions similar to other economic depressions.'' -RRB-. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> `` Bear'' <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>. <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> Shave signs -LRB- `` Missin' _ <PERSON> Kissin </PERSON>'? _ Perhaps Your Thrush _ Ca n't Get Thru _ The Underbrush _ Try _ <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> Shave'' -RRB-. _ C: Catfish -LRB- `` Southerners have never aligned themselves as closely with any cold-blooded creature as they have with the feline-looking catfish.'' -RRB- Chitterlings. <ORGANIZATION> Coca-Cola </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- once called `` the holy water of the American South'' -RRB-. Company towns -LRB- `` The right to occupancy was dependent upon employment. If out on strike, or ill, or injured, a worker and his family could be evicted on short notice.'' -RRB-. Confederate Memorial Day. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Racial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equality </ORGANIZATION>. Country Music Hall of Fame. <PERSON> Davy </PERSON> <PERSON> Crockett </PERSON>. Co-editor <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON> is astonished at the encyclopedia's instant popularity. A first printing of 15,000 sold out quickly; a second printing is in the works. He thinks it says something about the country that, despite the homogenizing effects of television, mobility, urbanity and the Interstate highway system, interest in regionalism is taking on new strength. `` A sense of being a Southerner, a New Yorker or Midwesterner persists,'' says <PERSON> Ferris </PERSON>. `` I think Americans are realizing that their regions are at the heart of their own identities as Americans.''
</TEXT>
