 <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Lakewood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, assembly plant will close in mid-March and production of the cars made there will shift to other plants, the company said Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> union swiftly criticized the decision, saying it `` sends a message of defeat and a message of failure'' in GM-UAW relations. The plant employs about 2,200 people, 250 of whom are salaried. About 1,000 of the employees are on indefinite layoff, a <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> statement said. Provisions are being made to ensure they get all the benefits to which they are entitled, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> said. `` We want to give our employees as much time as possible to prepare for this,'' said <PERSON> A.M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Beirne </PERSON>, head of manufacturing for <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Chevrolet-Pontiac-Canada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> The <LOCATION> Lakewood </LOCATION> plant makes the Chevrolet Caprice and the <ORGANIZATION> Buick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wagon </ORGANIZATION>. The Caprice also is made at <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, plant. <ORGANIZATION> Buick </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gustin </PERSON> said the station wagon will be built beyond mid-March, but he could n't say where. `` General Motors management is not trying nearly hard enough to fulfill its obligations under the national agreement and to source offshore production back into domestic plants if necessary to maintain employment here,'' said <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Yokich </PERSON>, in charge of the