<FIRST>r f PM-GATT-WorldTrade     09-15 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-GATT-World Trade,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Growth in World Trade Expected to Continue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The volume of world merchandise trade is expected to increase by about 7 percent in 1989 and growth will likely remain strong in the next few years, the organization that sponsors trade-liberalizing agreements said today. In an optimistic report, the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade said technological progress, the fall in the price of oil and new national economic policies were among factors behind `` unexpectedly high'' recent growth in international commerce. It said trade in services such as tourism and banking had grown even faster than merchandise trade during the 1980s and reached an estimated value of about $ 560 billion last year. Merchandise exports were worth an estimated $ 2.88 trillion in 1988, 14.5 percent higher than the previous year. The volume of goods traded increased by 8.5 percent, a record for the 1980s, the report said. Despite the expansion in world trade, many Third World countries suffered a drop in export earnings during the decade, the report said. It warned that the world's poorest countries can no longer rely on exports of commodities, which account for three-quarters of their foreign exchange, to fuel economic growth. Examining the reasons for the expansion of international commerce, <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> said one factor was technological innovations that have increased the scope of goods and services that can be traded on world markets. The halving of the price of oil since the 1980 peak, the rising share of manufactured products in trade, and the increase in the number of international mergers were also responsible, the report said. Economic reforms in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, relatively low inflation in Western countries, deregulation of business and freeing of capital movements further combined to boost world trade and open up international markets, the report said. In the longer term, <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> predicted the world economy `` may have entered a period in which the average growth rates for output and trade ... will be higher than they have been since the onset of economic difficulties in the late 1960s and the early 1970s.'' <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Woods </PERSON> said this forecast covered the next five to 10 years. The 97 nations that belong to the trade forum account for over four-fifths of world trade. <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION> became a member of <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> last month.
</TEXT>
