<FIRST>r f PM-CFC     09-15 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CFC,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Panel Backs Bill Aimed at Ozone-Depleting Chemical Makers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to legislation that would siphon off $ 4.3 billion over five years from profits of companies making ozone-depleting chemicals. The provision, approved Thursday, was added to a tax and entitlement bill. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has sought such a revenue-raising measure because it targets windfall profits that chemical firms could earn after an international treaty reduces supplies of chlorofluorocarbons. The so-called <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION>'s destroy the ozone layer in the stratosphere and increase the risk of skin cancer. There is similar language pending before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The proposal, which the Ways and Means panel labels a `` tax on ozone-depleting chemicals,'' would bring in an estimated $ 362 million in the 1990 fiscal year, while revenues in the following four years were put, respectively, at $ 614 million, $ 753 million, $ 1.1 billion and $ 1.4 billion. The tax would become effective Jan. 1. The chemical industry denies there will be windfall profits after the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> begins implementing the Montreal Protocol, a 1987 international agreement to cut production of <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION>'s The theory behind the tax is that demand will far outstrip supply once production is frozen at 1986 levels The protocol requires that by 1998, production can be only 50 percent of the 1986 figures. The five manufacturers of <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION>'s are developing substitutes, but they are reportedly three to five years away from production.
</TEXT>
