<SECOND>PM-Junk Bonds, Bjt,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Battered Junk Bond Market Awaits Campeau's Next Move</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The battered junk bond market is anxiously waiting to see whether <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> can snatch its prime retail operations from the precipice of default. <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Federated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> is scheduled to make a loan payment today reported to be in the $ 50 million range, but <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> needs an outside infusion of cash to prevent a default. In the junk bond market, where trading of the high-yield, high-risk securities took a gut-wrenching hit earlier this week, `` everybody is looking to see how <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> gets out of this mess, because it could have a big effect on everything,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Moran </PERSON>, a trader at <ORGANIZATION> Advest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. Admissions that both <PERSON> Federated </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Allied </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> units could default on their debt payments triggered a broad junk bond selloff earlier this week that spread to issues regarded as among the most stable and attractive. Critics have long contended that junk bonds, typically used to finance expensive, highly leveraged takeovers, were ripe for a fall. The thinking goes that companies would default on interest payments either because they would be unable to sell divisions at the heady prices they anticipated or because cash flows would not live up to expectations. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Campeau </PERSON>, head of the Toronto-based real estate and retail concern, was scrambling to line up financing from <ORGANIZATION> Olympia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Developments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> to pay the debt. Any success in getting more financing for Allied and <PERSON> Federated </PERSON>, which are in dire need of credit so they can stock up on inventory ahead of the Christmas shopping season, would help not only to prop up those precarious issues but the junk market in general. Traders fear that if the market is widely perceived as too risky and unstable, investors will dump their holdings. `` If too many people start jumping on the band wagon, the -LRB- junk-bond -RRB- mutual fund managers are not going to have enough cash to cover redemptions, and they're going to be forced to blow out of their positions,'' one observer said. So far traders said they had not detected any significant selling by mutual funds that invest in junk bonds. <PERSON> Moran </PERSON> said managers `` are studying the situation'' and are not likely to act hastily. `` Besides, the whole thing is up in the air,'' he said, noting that <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> could succeed in its restructuring plans. While some market experts said this week's selloff was particularly significant because more stable, attractive issues fell in tandem with distressed bonds, others contend the downturn was due. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Kidder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peabody </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yield </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Asset </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>, characterized the decline as more of a `` technical correction'' because prices had been on the upswing recently. Furthermore, there has been no change in the credit quality of most companies, he said. Yields quoted on some Allied and <PERSON> Federated </PERSON> issues have soared well above 25 percent to compensate for heightened risk. But, said <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Naylor </PERSON>, a senior vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Rodman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Renshaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, `` When a bond is trading at a 25 percent yield, it means they're not going to pay.'' <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> used billions of dollars from the sale of junk bonds to finance its $ 8.8 billion takeover of <PERSON> Federated </PERSON> last year. Not only did he pay top dollar for the retail company, but a stagnant consumer market dashed his plans for relying on cash flow to pay down the debt. Last week, <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> put its flagship <ORGANIZATION> Bloomingdale </ORGANIZATION>'s department store chain on the auction block in an effort to raise cash.
