<SECOND>PM-Milken-Leaks, Bjt,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Milken Lawyers Ask Court To Force Government To Stop Alleged Leaks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>'s lawyers say they are n't picking a fight with the press in an attempt to squelch alleged leaks by government prosecutors in the highly publicized securities fraud and racketeering case. In court papers filed this week, lawyers for the former <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> high-yield bond division leader claim that `` a constant stream'' of press leaks is threatening <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>'s right to a fair trial. The motion asks <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Kimba </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> to order the government to stop leaking confidential material, hold a hearing to identify the sources of the leaks, punish the leakers and make public a confidential <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> memo written about in <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. No members of the media would be called at any hearing on the motion because `` we are not interested in confrontations with the press,'' the motion adds. The lawyers claim the government has turned confidential grand jury proceedings into `` a spectator sport'' by releasing information about the <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> probe repeatedly over the last three years to pressure witnesses and other possible targets to cooperate. The motion, filed Wednesday in federal court in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>, claims the alleged leaking `` flatly violates'' federal criminal regulations and other legal and ethical rules requiring confidentiality in government investigations. `` We are asking the court to stop the government from continuing its leaking and to punish those government officials responsible,'' <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Flumenbaum </PERSON>, a lawyer for <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, said Thursday. A hearing to ferret out media leaks would not be unprecedented. The motion cites the 1980 bank fraud case of former <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration budget director <PERSON> Bert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lance </PERSON>, in which a federal appeals court ordered such a hearing. Though the <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> motion seeks to exclude reporters, `` Motions like this have the potential for leading to First Amendment confrontations with the press,'' according to one prominent First Amendment attorney, who asked not to be identified. <PERSON> Milken </PERSON>, his brother, <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON>, and former <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> trader <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Newberg </PERSON> were charged March 29 in a 98-count fraud and racketeering indictment that alleges insider trading, securities law violations and other crimes in the broadest action of the government's Wall Street crackdown. They pleaded innocent and a March 1990 trial is set. <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> was first named in news reports as the government's main target shortly after now-jailed stock speculator <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> agreed to cooperate with prosecutors in late 1986. Newspaper stories since then regularly have contained advance details of the government's investigation and indictment plans, including the charges. The <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> motion cites stories published in The Wall Street Journal, The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> about the case quoting `` sources close to the investigation'' or `` people familiar with the government's investigation.'' <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> May </PERSON>, spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Co.. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns The <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>, said the newspaper does not comment on its sourcing policies `` Our job is to try to find out what people are doing. That's what we do, added <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Baron </PERSON>, business editor of The Los Angeles Times The 31-page motion states that, `` The government has presented _ and is continuing to present _ its case to the grand jurors as much through the pages of the daily papers as through the testimony of witnesses in the grand jury room.'' The document cites three recent stories in the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> based on a confidential May 1988 <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> report containing details of secret testimony of government witnesses, and other articles specifying the contents of a new <PERSON> Milken </PERSON> indictment expected in October. The leaks are the result of `` decisions by some in the government to use publicity as a prosecutorial weapon, carefully timing the disclosures to ` pressure' defendants, witnesses and those under investigation,'' the motion states. An <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman declined to comment on the memo. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's said it would respond to the motion in court.
