<SECOND>PM-SEC-Breeden, Bjt,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Breeden: SEC Staff Needs More Money to Remain Competitive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s choice for chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, pledges to crack down hard on inside traders but says his No. 1 problem is improving the pay of the agency's staff. The nominee told senators at his confirmation hearing Thursday that he would `` absolutely'' continue the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>'s current efforts `` to root fraud out of the securities markets.'' But <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> also said pay increases for <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> staffers were necessary to attract new talent and cut the agency's high turnover rate. `` I do n't know of any single issue facing the commission today that is more important than our ability to maintain the caliber and the quality of the staff,'' <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> said. The starting salary for an <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> staff attorney is $ 27,130 _ well below what a top law school graduate can make at a Wall Street law firm, <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> officials said. In a morning-long hearing before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>, who once headed a task force on deregulation of the financial industry, said he believed in free, competitive markets. But, he added, `` Free markets do n't work if investors or participants believe they are dominated by fraud or corruption.'' The committee will decide if <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>'s nomination should be recommended to the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. `` I think you can do an exceptional job, but it wo n't be easy,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON>, D-Mich., adding that he intended to vote for <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>'s confirmation After the hearing, <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> told reporters he expected a confirmation vote would come `` in a few days.'' <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> noted <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> still had to supply detailed answers to written questions posed by the committee staff. <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>, a White House aide who helped write the legislation to bail out the nation's savings and loan industry, was tapped by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> for the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> post last month. At the time, <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> and other senators expressed skepticism about the banking lawyer's experience in the securities industry. But the promised public grilling of the nominee never materialized, apparently due to <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>'s impressive performance in private meetings with committee members earlier this week. Several senators remarked about those private meetings in praising <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON>'s intelligence and candor during the hearing. <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> told Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, D-Conn., that it's `` a perfectly legitimate role of government to keep the markets clean. He said that would restore individual investors' confidence in the markets and attract foreign investment. When <PERSON> Riegle </PERSON> expressed hope that wrongdoers would find <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> a `` fair but tough cop on the beat,'' <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> replied, `` Certainly, if I am fortunate enough to be confirmed, under my leadership that will be the case.'' <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> appeared relaxed but cautious as he answered committee members' questions, constantly asserting that his views were his own and he could n't speak for the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>. He said the $ 200 billion junk bond market `` is worth the careful attention of the commission'' although he was `` not suggesting there's any particular problem in the market today.'' <PERSON> Breeden </PERSON> also said he did n't think the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> had been `` overzealous'' in its pursuit of insider trading and said the charges against the investment banking giant <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> were for more than `` harmless technical problems.'' He said the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> and the rival <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> should remain separate agencies and called for a better working relationship, including staff exchanges, with the <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION>, which has disputed the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> jurisdiction over some new financial instruments that have elements of both securities and futures contracts.
