<FIRST>r f PM-Curtiss-Wright     09-15 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Curtiss-Wright,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Contractor Agrees to Pay $1.4 Million Civil Fine, Official
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL MORAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s chief supplier of hydraulic aircraft landing gear has agreed to repay the government about $ 1.4 million in contract overcharges for the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>'s largest transport plane. The government claimed that labor charges on a $ 6.7 million contract were twice as high as original estimates by the company, <ORGANIZATION> Curtiss-Wright </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Ridgefield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Alito </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr </PERSON>. The contract was for 60 spare landing gear actuators that control landing gear, flaps and other moveable exterior systems on the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> C-5A Galaxy. <PERSON> Alito </PERSON> said the company's failure to provide <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> auditors with labor standards and data on the company's internal cost estimates `` led to a gross inflation of the labor costs.'' Curtiss-Wright has denied any wrongdoing. Attempts to reach corporate officials after the settlement was announced Thursday evening were unsuccessful and the switchboard at the company's headquarters was closed The government contends <ORGANIZATION> Curtiss-Wright </ORGANIZATION>'s contract was based on a company estimate of 46,000 labor hours for the contract. <PERSON> Alito </PERSON> said investigators found the contract was completed in 23,000 hours. `` The company's failure to live up to its certification with respect to the C-5A flight actuators subjected it to civil liability,'' <PERSON> Alito </PERSON> said in a statement. Under the False Claims Act, a Civil War-era statute aimed at wartime profiteers, the government can demand reimbursement when it can prove a contractor was not negotiated in good faith. The act was further bolstered in 1986 by amendments that allow the government to claim triple damages and apply large fines. <PERSON> Alito </PERSON> said the claims were not part of criminal or civil court proceedings but were the result of a preliminary investigation by his office and the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investigative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, an arm of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>.
