<HEAD>Ex-Chairman Pleads Guilty to Scheme to Sell Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The former head of <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has pleaded guilty to conspiracy and wire fraud for his role in a scheme to try to sell confidential company documents. <PERSON> Orin </PERSON> <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON>, 65, of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, entered the plea in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday. He faces a maximum of 10 years in prison and a $ 500,00 fine when sentenced Nov. 16. An attorney whose firm once worked for <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> was indicted Thursday for his alleged role in the same scheme. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Benito </PERSON> <PERSON> Romano </PERSON> said <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> and the lawyer, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON>, were involved in a secret scheme to defraud <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> by attempting to sell confidential papers to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iranian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which was involved in a dispute with <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION>. The documents dealt with the 1979 sale of $ 283 million in crude oil from the Iranian company to <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Overseas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary in <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION>. Court papers said <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> never paid for the oil. <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> was <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive from 1974 to 1981. He was a consultant to <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION>, earning $ 425,000 a year, from 1981 to 1984. In 1982, while he was a paid consultant, <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> received about 260 privileged documents about the oil sale through an unidentified <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> employee, <PERSON> Romano </PERSON> said. According to the indictment against <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON>, <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> and <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON> made repeated attempts from 1982 to 1988 to sell the documents and <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON>' consulting services to the Iranian company. They had planned to use a Swiss bank account to receive their payment, it said. As compensation, <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> and <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON> asked for 25 percent of the Iranian company's recovery from <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION>, the indictment alleged. In court Thursday, <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> said the deal was never finalized although representatives of the Iranian company were allowed to view the documents in 1985. After seeing the papers, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iranian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> sued <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> Overseas for payment on the oil. Those suits, filed in <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Bermuda </LOCATION>, were settled last week when <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> agreed to pay $ 325 million, said Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Herve </PERSON> <PERSON> Gouraige </PERSON>. Neither Ashland or <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iranian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> were charged with any wrongdoing. <PERSON> Romano </PERSON> praised the cooperation of Ashland in the investigation. <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON>, 38, of <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, was charged with conspiracy and six counts of wire fraud. If convicted, he faces five years in prison and a $ 250,000 fine on each count. He was not in custody and was scheduled to be arraigned Sept. 21. An earlier complaint charging <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON> and former <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> vice president <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Dugan </PERSON> with interstate transportation of stolen property was dismissed during the investigation that led to the latest charges. <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON> was identifed as a former partner in the law firm of <ORGANIZATION> Barnett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> Alagia </LOCATION>, based in <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, with offices around the country. The indictment said the firm represented <ORGANIZATION> Ashland </ORGANIZATION> in certain legal matters while <PERSON> Atkins </PERSON> was chairman. <PERSON> Gouraige </PERSON> declined to discuss why the earlier complaint against <PERSON> Barnett </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dugan </PERSON> was dismissed.
