<BYLINE>By DAN BLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has launched a restructuring program that will trim as many as 1,200 managers from the workforce despite years of steady profit growth. The regional telephone company announced Thursday it would offer early retirement incentives aimed at cutting 1,000 to 1,200 managers and said it is also considering several financial moves such as refinancing some debts and revaluing spare parts inventories. The reorganization will lead to the company's first quarterly drop in profit since it was created in 1984 by the breakup of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> will break even or make a small profit in the fourth quarter, officials said For the same period last year, the company made $ 1.53 per share. In the second quarter of this year, the company's net income rose 4.9 percent to $ 360.8 million, or $ 1.84 per share. `` We think the time to change is when you're doing well,'' said <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Mollura </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. `` If you wait until things go bad, it's too late.'' `` In a very real sense we are laying the groundwork for the <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> of the future,'' <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman and chief executive, said in a news release. Managers will be offered cash incentives and pension benefits to retire early, the company said. The company will eliminate one level of management, based in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, overseeing the <LOCATI