TION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> chief financial officer. <PERSON> Pitt </PERSON> said the recent three-week strike by members of the <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brotherhood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electrical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> against <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> played no part in the restructuring decision or its timing. <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION>'s seven subsidiaries are <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Diamond </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Chesapeake </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Potomac </LOCATION> companies in <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>.
