<HEAD>Mitsubishi Bank to List on New York Stock Exchange Next Week</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> next week will become the first Japanese bank to be listed on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> and also will rank as the largest foreign company traded on the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, published reports said Friday. <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION>, the world's fourth-largest bank, will be the ninth Japanese company to be listed on the <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION>, according to the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. American investors will be allowed to trade more than two billion <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> shares, which initially will trade in the form of American depository receipts, the paper said. The move marks the first attempt by a Japanese bank to raise money in the American capital markets, which some Wall Street observers have predicted would be a growing trend, the paper said. The major Japanese banks are under pressure to raise $ 35 billion over the next four years in order to comply with new capital requirements that the world's leading central banks have set for international banks. The Times noted that Japanese banks had not been expected to resort to the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> to raise capital because they would have to meet <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> disclosure requirements as well as alter their accounting practices. But <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> has met the requirements. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, the economic newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Nihon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Keizai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shimbun </ORGANIZATION> said the listing would be made on Sept. 19. Established in 1919, <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> had assets totalling about $ 343.2 billion and net income of $ 1.15 billion for the fiscal year ended March 31, according to a company report. The Tokyo-based bank has 245 domestic offices and 37 overseas affiliates in 24 countries. <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> and Japanese government officials were not available for comment Friday, which was a national holiday in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>.
