<HEAD>$adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday Sept. 18 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Broken 7-Iron Inspiration For Las Vegas Discount Golf Chain</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Voss </PERSON> <PERSON> Boreta </PERSON> was a failed casino host between jobs when a broken 7-iron got him off the golf course and into the golf equipment business. Fifteen years later, he heads one of the country's biggest golf retailing outfits, one now poised to enter the lucrative Japanese market with a chain of 30 new stores. `` We were just going to have a little store,'' <PERSON> Boreta </PERSON> said of the humble beginnings of his <ORGANIZATION> Las </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vegas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Discount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Golf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Tennis empire. `` It's just kind of grown from there.'' From the 1,200-square-foot store tucked in the corner of an aging shopping center, <PERSON> Boreta </PERSON>'s discount golf outfit has grown into a multimillion-dollar operation with 42 franchises nationwide and 13 more ready to open this year. The chain, riding a nationwide boom in golf, did $ 47 million in business in 1988, $ 12 million of that at its main <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> store alone, ranking it near the top golf equipment retailers in the country. Not bad for a one-time avid golfer who does n't even play the game anymore. `` I have n't played since 1975,'' <PERSON> Boreta </PERSON> said recently in an interview in his cramped and cluttered office in the back of the original store. `` With the company growing like it has, I did n't have the time to devote to playing. Timing has been everything for the 52-year-old <PERSON> Boreta </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> nightclub operator who freely admits he stumbled into the golf game almost by accident. <PERSON> Boreta </PERSON> came to <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> in 1974 to become a casino host at the Tropicana Hotel. But, after three days, he decided the job did n't suit him and spent his days playing golf while deciding his future plans `` One day I broke a 7-iron and there was no place to fix it,'' <PERSON> Boreta </PERSON> recalled. `` I sent it to a friend who ran a golf shop in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and told him there was a great opportunity here. He said, ` Why do n't you do it?''' <PERSON> Boreta </PERSON> took the advice and opened the original <ORGANIZATION> Las </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vegas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Discount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Golf </ORGANIZATION> store in a shopping center near the Las Vegas airport. The store grossed $ 275,000 the first year and <PERSON> Boreta </PERSON> was off and running. It was a tenative step into mail order two years later, however, that put the company name on the national map and on its way to being a major player in the golf equipment business. `` We put a little ad in <ORGANIZATION> Golf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Digest </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- magazine -RRB- that people had to call with their own dime,'' <PERSON> Boreta </PERSON> said. `` When they called, we told them we'd send them a catalog when we did n't even have one put together yet. But the next thing you know, here comes a couple of orders in.'' Ironically, one of the country's largest golf mail-order outlets and franchisers, <ORGANIZATION> Nevada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bob </ORGANIZATION>'s, also got its start in <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>. At the same time the discount golf shops were beginning to expand, golf club manufacturers were broadening their club lines to tap the beginners market. `` These manufacturers got smart and started making game improvement clubs,'' <PERSON> Boreta </PERSON> said. `` That is what really started the golfing boom. Now, you can take a non-player and after one lesson he can hit the ball in the air and in the general direction he or she wants it.'' Those clubs have been constantly improving and Japanese companies have taken the lead in marrying boron and graphite shafts that are stronger, longer and more accurate than their steel predecessors. Partly as a result, according to the Florida-based <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Golf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, some 23.4 million people played at least one round of golf last year, up from 15.1 million in 1980. More than 320 new courses have opened since 1987 in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, bringing the total to more than 13,000. In <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, there are an estimated 12 million golfers and 1,600 courses. `` I've never seen anything like the last few years as far as people playing the game,'' <PERSON> Boreta </PERSON> said. `` It seems like just in the last two years it has really taken off.'' <PERSON> Boreta </PERSON> sees an even bigger opportunity in the lucrative Japanese market and his chain has signed an agreement with a Japanese company to open a store in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> next month followed by 29 others for other locations in the golf-crazy country.'' `` We get a tremendous amount of Japanese who come here and buy three or four sets of clubs and take them home to sell to friends,'' <PERSON> Boreta </PERSON> said. `` We figured we'd take the operation to them.''
</TEXT>
