<HEAD>Imports Down in July</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Steel imports fell 5.9 percent to 1.46 million tons in July compared with the previous month and represented 19.3 percent of the domestic supply, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> reported Friday. Steel imports for the first seven months of 1989 were 10.2 million tons, down 19.7 percent from the same period last year and representing 17.5 percent of domestic supply, the trade group reported. Steel exports in July amounted to 303,000 tons, down 24.8 percent from June, the group said. In July 1988, American steel manufacturers exported 128,000 tons. The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Imported </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which represents leading steel importers and exporters, said imports for the first seven months amounted to 15.2 percent of domestic demand when semifinished steel bound for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mills is excluded. The steel import group noted the percentage without semifinished steel is below the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration's Voluntary Restraint Agreements target of 18.5 percent of imported steel in the domestic market.
