<HEAD>Cable Operator to Debut Independent Station</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An independent television station being launched by a local cable operator could signal the opening of a new battleground between cable and free television. WGRC-TV, scheduled to debut Thursday in <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, will air syndicated network reruns, sports, movies, and locally produced children's shows. The station hopes eventually to debut a local newscast and is negotiating to broadcast some <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mets </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Yankees </ORGANIZATION> games. `` It's an expansion of cable's promise, which is to deliver programming choice to subscribers,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Alter </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advertising </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` It's providing expanded, enriched service that is very localized.'' The station will be programmed and operated by local cable operator <ORGANIZATION> Greater </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rochester </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cablevision </ORGANIZATION>, which currently reaches 62 percent of the area's households with televisions. The <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION> market has one non-cable independent station. Alter predicted that if the <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION> station is successful, independent stations will be launched in other markets. Some cable operators have already begun airing local news shows, he said. <PERSON> Lana </PERSON> <PERSON> King </PERSON>, marketing vice president for the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stations </ORGANIZATION>, reacted with dismay to the advent of the new station and the possibility of others like it. `` This threatens our ability to serve the community free of charge,'' she said. `` It's a fear that we have had for a long time.'' <PERSON> King </PERSON> said that cable stations, with the added revenue from subscriber charges as well as advertising, can outbid independent television stations for syndicated programming. Eventually, she said, viewers could end up having to pay to see the same programs they would have gotten for free. `` We're seeing it happening in sports,'' she said. `` That same phenomenon is now happening in all programming.'' The <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION> cable station currently carries locally originated programming like fishing shows. <ORGANIZATION> GRC </ORGANIZATION> President and chief executive officer <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiaino </PERSON> said the idea for the station originated in <LOCATION> Rochester </LOCATION>, but that <ORGANIZATION> GRC </ORGANIZATION>'s parent company, <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, will be `` watching what we do with interest.'' The station was created to increase advertising revenues and subscribers and in response to new syndication laws, <PERSON> Chiaino </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> may sell advertising on the station in packages with its other products, including Sports Illustrated and Time magazines, according to <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murtagh </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Seltel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a sales representative for the station.
