<SECOND>BC-Sharon Steel, Adv 18,0911</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday Sept. 18</HEAD>
<HEAD>Workers Unconvinced By Tale of Woe, Laying the Basis For Showdown</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FARRELL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Sharon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s chief operating officer would have people believe his company is failing when times are good. True or not, <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kern </PERSON>'s view is rejected by employees who will soon be asked by company negotiators to grant a third consecutive round of contract concessions. `` I do n't believe it, not one bit of it,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, 56, of <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON>, a veteran of nearly 30 years with the company. `` They're cutthroats. <PERSON> Kern </PERSON> says the company's ability to persuade the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steelworkers </ORGANIZATION> union could determine whether <ORGANIZATION> Sharon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> rises from Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization or is liquidated under Chapter 7. That in turn will influence the economy of this steelmaking area of western <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, into which <ORGANIZATION> Sharon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> pumps about $ 200 million annually as one of the largest employers with 2,600 workers. `` We lost money in the best steel market in a decade and have the dubious distinction of being the only company to say that. That gives you an idea of the destitute situation here,'' <PERSON> Kern </PERSON> said in a recent interview in his spartan office. The nation's 16th-largest steelmaker has been trying to reorganize under Chapter 11 of the bankruptcy laws since April 17, 1987, listing $ 740 million in debts it could not pay. <PERSON> Kern </PERSON>'s plan for saving the company begins with lowering employment costs by cutting direct cash outlays and erasing what he calls wasteful and inefficient work rules. New equipment would come later. `` A contract has to be clearly in sight by Thanksgiving and ratified by no later than January or February or we will face a number of things,'' he said. By early next year, <PERSON> Kern </PERSON> said, the company could run out of cash and be forced to delay bill payments, echoing events that forced it into bankruptcy court two years ago. `` We're that close if the market stays soft, and I think it will get softer,'' said <PERSON> Kern </PERSON>, a 14-year veteran of <ORGANIZATION> Sharon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> management who left in 1982 and returned in late April as chief operating officer. It was not clear when contract talks would begin. <ORGANIZATION> Sharon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> owes $ 70 million to pension plans for 3,500 retirees, and total labor costs are around $ 28 per hour, among the highest even for major producers, said <PERSON> Phil </PERSON> <PERSON> Smalley </PERSON>, vice president of industrial relations. The company's steel and steel-related segments lost $ 16.3 million on sales of $ 263.1 million during the first half of this year, according to the court-appointed trustee serving as chief executive. The company's non-steel operations _ copper and brass fabrication at <ORGANIZATION> Mueller </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and coal mining at <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fuel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and gold mining at <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> _ continue to offset much of steel's losses and helped limit the first-half consolidated net loss to $ 2.5 million `` How can they not be making money?'' said <ORGANIZATION> Sharon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> veteran Bud Pears. `` Guys are working overtime out their ears. We're producing steel like crazy'' Workers say there are plenty of signs that the company is making money <ORGANIZATION> Sharon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> expanded its workforce to 2,600 by early this year to meet demand for its products. Average shipments climbed from 70,000 tons per month in 1987 to 89,000 last year and were running at 92,000 tons per month through the first half of this year. The steel industry is enjoying its third year of recovery. And <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Posner </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> financier accused of sucking <ORGANIZATION> Sharon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> dry of cash after acquiring control, still owns the stock but has been stripped of his authority. `` People say, ` Who are you kidding?''' <PERSON> Kern </PERSON> said, acknowledging the skepticism. `` I say even in the good days, <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> was one of the laggards.'' A landlocked blast furnace, for which iron ore, coke and limestone must be delivered by rail and truck instead of cheaper barge transportation, is one of the disadvantages that <PERSON> Kern </PERSON> calls congenital defects. `` Near-Neanderthal tools,'' an unwieldy product mix and work rules that inflate production costs also work against the company, he said. `` The market is weaker, and prices are softening, and the loss rate is accelerating,'' <PERSON> Kern </PERSON> said. `` We're losing money, dissipating assets.'' Management sees another crunch coming, and warns employees in a series of red-lettered pamphlets that without large sums of money to buy new equipment, lower labor costs may be the only hope of avoiding Chapter 7 liquidation. `` Not as far as I'm concerned,'' said <PERSON> Pears </PERSON>. `` I do n't care what they do. I'm just down there working. When it's over, it's over. I'll go find the next job.'' Pears and others say they're particularly bitter about an employee stock ownership plan that the employees say is overdue in repaying their investments. `` I've got $ 16,000 in it, and I'll never see it,'' said Pears. `` So you tell me how you'd feel towards the place. Bottom line.'' Even those workers who are convinced <ORGANIZATION> Sharon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> is in trouble do n't sound sympathetic. `` As far as concessions are concerned, I do believe they need them. But as far as I'm concerned they're not going to get them,'' said <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Ivanovich </PERSON> of <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON>. `` I gave and gave. There's no more to give.''
</TEXT>
