<HEAD>Hoylake Gets More Time for Its BAT Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s takeover watchdog, recognizing the increasingly international nature of the bidding process, on Friday allowed <ORGANIZATION> Hoylake </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investments </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION> more time for its $ 21 billion bid for <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. In an unprecedented step, the Panel on Takeovers and Mergers, which imposes a complex timetable on takeovers in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, said it would allow <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> to rebid for BAT after it obtains approval from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> state insurance regulators to change the ownership of <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> It said delays by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> regulatory process meant BAT shareholders were not able to properly consider the offer of 878 pence, or $ 13.52, a share in securities. The purchase would be the world's second-largest takeover after <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 24.5 billion acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> RJR </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nabisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. BAT, a British conglomerate with interests in tobacco, retailing, financial services and paper, said it would take the ruling to the panel's appeal committee. That stops the current <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> takeover clock until a final decision is reached. BAT's shares soared on the developments. They rose 18 pence, or 28 cents, to 819 pence, or $ 12.61, a share on <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on Friday. <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> still must win the green light from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> regulators. In addition, <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> probably would have to increase its offer or include some cash to lure BAT's shareholders, analysts have said. BAT attacked the panel's decision, saying it undermined the watchdog's goal of protecting targets from `` an indefinite and damaging siege.'' <PERSON> Hoylake </PERSON> said it welcomed the news and that Anglo-French financier Sir <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON>, who is spearheading the bidding group, would depart immediately for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` to establish the best way to continue to expedite the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> regulatory approval.'' <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON> is to meet with <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Bebear </PERSON>, chairman of the French insurance giant <ORGANIZATION> Axa-Midi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assurances </ORGANIZATION>, which wants to buy Farmers under <ORGANIZATION> Hoylake </ORGANIZATION>'s proposed break-up of BAT. <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> says it wants to sell off all of <ORGANIZATION> BAT </ORGANIZATION>'s non-tobacco assets. Other investors in <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> include <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> merchant banker <PERSON> Jacob </PERSON> <PERSON> Rothschild </PERSON> and Australian entrepreneur <PERSON> Kerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Packer </PERSON>. Concern has grown in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> over interference from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> regulators and courts in takeover fights involving British companies with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interests. South African-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SA </ORGANIZATION>'s bid for the British mining group <ORGANIZATION> Consolidated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gold </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fields </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> failed earlier this year because the offer expired under British takeover rules while it was being reviewed in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> federal court. Under the panel's rules, <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION>, which launched its offer for BAT on July 11, had had until Oct. 7 to obtain a majority stake in BAT. If it had failed, it would have had to wait for a year to bid again. The panel, after holding a full hearing on Wednesday, said Friday morning that it would allow <ORGANIZATION> Hoylake </ORGANIZATION> 21 days to complete its bid for BAT after it wins <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> approval. The panel has altered its timetable in the past under varying conditions, but it has never before granted an extension because of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> regulatory holdups, said a panel official, who asked not to be identified, in accordance with British practice. Explaining its decision, the panel said the delay caused by the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proceedings meant BAT shareholders were not getting a real opportunity to consider the offer on its merits. `` One of the principal objects of the code is to enable the shareholders in the target company to have an opportunity to consider an offer for their company on its merits on an informed basis in an orderly and limited time scale,'' the panel said. BAT Chairman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> said BAT did n't want to deprive its shareholders of the opportunity to consider a bid. `` We are simply seeking to remove the uncertainty, and also the damage which a prolonged siege would inflict on the company,'' <PERSON> Sheehy </PERSON> said. BAT said the panel's `` wrong decision'' allows <LOCATION> Hoylake </LOCATION> to free itself from regulatory difficulties which are `` entirely of its own making.''
