<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chris-Craft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said Friday it was appealing a <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> judge's ruling that the company, a major shareholder in <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, has no power to veto the merger between <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The ruling last week by <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said the terms of a class of <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> preferred stock held by a <ORGANIZATION> Chris-Craft </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, <ORGANIZATION> BHC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, did not entitle Chris-Craft to vote on the merger of the two media giants. A Chris-Craft attorney, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crompton </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, said the company was asking the <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to overturn the ruling on the ground <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> had inaccurately interpreted the terms of the stock. A three-judge panel of the state's highest court was to hear arguments in the case on Oct. 18 in <LOCATION> Dover </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> ruled in response to a request for a declaration of Chris-Craft's rights by <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>, who want the issue resolved so they can consummate their merger. <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> completed a $ 14 billion tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> in July, and then changed its name to <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The companies hope to finalize their merger later this year. A decision by <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, later upheld by the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, threw out a challenge to the merger by <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which had sought to acquire <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 12 billion. In his latest decision, <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> said that under the terms of the stock Chris-Craft does not `` possess a veto over every merger in which its interests would be adversely affected.'' Chris-Craft contended it had a right to vote on the merger because its preferred <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> shares can be converted into preferred <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> shares. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Chris-Craft </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON> have been feuding since Chris-Craft helped <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> fend off an unwanted takeover bid from publisher <PERSON> Rupert </PERSON> <PERSON> Murdoch </PERSON> in 1984.
