<HEAD>Dollar Falls In Panicky Domestic Dealings</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede: LONDON</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar fell sharply Friday in panicky domestic dealings characterized by wild rumors and price swings, erasing gains posted in earlier foreign trading. Gold prices were mixed. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, gold bullion for current delivery jumped to $ 363.90 a troy ounce, up $ 3.40 from Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> quoted a late bid for gold of $ 362.50 an ounce, up from $ 359.35. The dollar rallied sharply in foreign trading, climbing above the benchmark 2.00 level against the West German mark following a better-than-expected report on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the deficit narrowed to a seasonally adjusted $ 7.58 billion in August from a revised $ 8.01 billion in July, shocking a market that had expected a $ 9 billion shortfall. But traders at home said the euphoria was short-lived. By mid-afternoon, the market was hit with a string of outrageous rumors ranging from the assassination of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to the failure of <ORGANIZATION> Wells </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fargo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` With the slew of rumors, the dollar came screaming off,'' said <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrie </PERSON>, a vice president at the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office. `` It was scary.'' Within an hour, the dollar plunged 6 pfennigs against the West German mark. `` That's a pretty dramatic move,'' said <PERSON> Earl </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, a vice president at <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` We were sitting at 2.00 marks _ it was a wild and crazy day.'' One by one the rumors were denied, which helped pick the dollar up from its lows. But <PERSON> Lawrie </PERSON> said many investors had been `` scared enough today to step out of their positions and take a breather.'' The central banks joined forces to sell dollars throughout the day, and ultimately traders welcomed the move for smoothing out the dollar's decline. The session's extreme volatility has forced technicians to revise their trading ranges. `` It will be a while before we test 2.00 marks again,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. Fundamentally, dealers noted that the trade report showed a decline in both imports and exports, perhaps pointing to a weakening economy and lower interest rates, which do not bode well for the dollar. The yen was not traded Friday in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where markets were closed for a holiday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar was quoted at 148.65 yen, compared with Thursday's closing price in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> of 145.85 yen. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the dollar closed at 146.35 yen, down from 146.85 yen on Thursday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost $ 1.5390 to buy one pound, cheaper than $ 1.5582 late Thursday. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, it cost $ 1.5660 to buy one pound, more expensive than Thursday's $ 1.5540. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, compared with late rates Thursday, included: 1.9660 West German marks, down from 1.9750; 1.6945 Swiss francs, down from 1.7040; 6.6295 French francs, down from 6.6615; 1,410.50 Italian lire, down from 1,418.50, and 1.1848 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1850. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, compared with late rates Thursday, included: 2.0005 West German marks, up from 1.9705; 1.7260 Swiss francs, up from 1.7000; 6.7430 French francs, up from 6.6485; 2.2490 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2185; 1,433.00 Italian lire, up from 1,413.00; and 1.1880 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1849. Gold fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to a late bid of $ 356.25 a troy ounce, compared with late Thursday's $ 362.00. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, gold fell to $ 356.00 an ounce from $ 361.75 late Thursday. <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s gold market was closed Friday for the Chinese mid-autumn festival. Silver prices were mixed. On <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s Comex, silver bullion for current delivery rose to $ 5.084 an ounce from $ 5.055 Thursday. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the metal was trading at a late bid of $ 5.03 a troy ounce, compared with Thursday's $ 5.12.
