<HEAD>Energy Futures Rise on Late Buying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Energy futures prices resumed their upward climb Friday after one trader entered the gasoline market in late afternoon and sparked activity in crude and heating oil futures. The October contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, rose 24 cents to $ 19.96 a 42-gallon barrel on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Among refined products traded on the exchange, the October contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline picked up 0.94 cent to close at 57.61 cents a gallon and home heating oil for October delivery rose 0.91 cent to settle at 55.95 cents a gallon. On Thursday, energy futures, which have rallied in recent weeks, paused for a round of profit-taking, and for much of Friday's session, the market was quiet However, in late afternoon, one trader began buying the October contract for gasoline, and `` ran it up to a level where they got everyone else's interest,'' said <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Dreis </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Merrill </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lynch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION>. `` Crude and heating oil had to come up with it,'' <PERSON> Dreis </PERSON> said. There were no news developments to influence trading, he said.
