<HEAD>Rumors Wrench Gold Market, Which Ends Higher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Gold futures prices made strong gains Friday on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> after being wrenched back from three-year lows by unfounded rumors that President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had been shot and that a major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> bank was near collapse `` From what we can see it was purely rumor-driven,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Jonat </PERSON>, a metals trader with <ORGANIZATION> Deak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. On other markets, energy futures advanced; grains and soybeans were mixed; and livestock and meat futures were mixed Gold futures settled $ 3.40 higher across the board with the contract for delivery in October at $ 365.20 a troy ounce. Silver futures were 2.7 cents to 2.9 cents higher with September at $ 5.084 a troy ounce. Analysts said the moves in the metal markets were mainly reactions to the dollar, which strengthened early in the day following positive reports on inflation and the trade deficit, then collapsed in the afternoon amid the wild rumors. `` We had a complete reversal,'' said <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Sloane </PERSON>, a metals analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` The dollar went through what was described as a free fall.'' The market gave more credence to the talk of an impending bank collapse than to the rumors about <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, analysts said, because the financial markets already were jittery about the credit troubles of retailing giant <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGAN