<HEAD>Minority Broadcast Rules Need Congressional Protection, Senate Panel
Told</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> rules that have increased minority and female ownership of radio and TV stations need congressional protection from recent attacks in the courts and from the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> itself, a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel was told Friday. Minority and women broadcasters said they had made great strides in gaining licenses during the 1970s when the rules were established to ease their entry, but that progress slowed under the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration during the early 1980s. The Republican-led FCC `` began a concerted attack upon minority ownership polices. ... Eight years after the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration took office there are only 160 radio stations and 15 television stations'' owned by blacks, which represents 2 percent of all stations, said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Winston </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Owned </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasters </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1988 ordered the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> to stop reconsidering the minority and female preference rules, but the rules suffered a major blow earlier this year when a court declared part of them unconstitutional. Witnesses urged the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> communications subcommittee to write the FCC rules into law to protect them from constitutional attack. Subcommittee chairman Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Hawaii </LOCATION>, said his staff was preparing such legislation. `` In the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> got on the wrong track,'' Sen. <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-S.C. </LOCATION>, the full <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> committee </ORGANIZATION> chairman, said in written testimony. `` While it used fancy words and phrases to claim these policies were unconstitutional, we knew all along it simply did not support the spirit of these policies.'' <PERSON> Hollings </PERSON> said a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> appropriations subcommittee this week included a provision in an <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> appropriations bill that would maintain the rules. The FCC rules, first adopted in 1973, give preference to minorities and women in license renewal proceedings. In 1978, the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> added an important provision that gives a tax break to station owners who sell to minorities. `` If the tax certificate policy is ever eliminated, minority purchasers might as well disconnect their telephones, because they will never get another call to purchase a station,'' <ORGANIZATION> Winston </ORGANIZATION> said. Another provision added in 1978 was the distress sale policy that allows broadcasters facing license revocation to sell quickly to minority groups for 75 percent of the fair value of the station and end further FCC action against them. But the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> appeals court in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> this year struck down the policy, saying the <ORGANIZATION> FCC </ORGANIZATION> had not demonstrated there was a link between minority ownership and a proliferation of minority programming and that the agency had not demonstrated there is a history of racial discrimination in broadcasting requiring the preference policies. Less than a month later, however, another three-judge panel of the court upheld the constitutionality of the female and minority preference provisions. The lone witness testifying against codifying the rules was <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Shurberg </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Hartford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, broadcaster who won the appeals court test. <PERSON> Shurberg </PERSON>, who opposed a minority broadcaster who had won station <ORGANIZATION> WHCT-TV </ORGANIZATION> in a distress sale, cited the court's view that without firm evidence that would-be minority owners are subject to discrimination when they try to buy stations, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should not intervene. He said minorities do n't necessarily program for the benefit of minorities once they've achieved their licenses, particularly if the station is located in a market made up of primarily non-minority listeners. `` Diversity is driven by the marketplace,'' <PERSON> Shurberg </PERSON> said.
