<HEAD>Bond Prices Up After Uneven Session</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bond prices gyrated Friday before finishing higher in a session dominated by mixed economic news and rumors. The <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>'s benchmark 30-year bond was up in early trading, down slightly at midday, and back up by the close. It finished 15-32 point higher, or nearly $ 4.70 per $ 1,000 face amount. Its yield, which falls when prices rise, fell to 8.07 percent from 8.12 percent late Thursday. Analysts said bonds got their first boost from the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Producer Price Index, which showed wholesale prices falling in August for the third consecutive month, down 0.4 percent. But bonds dropped later when traders noted that excluding the volatile food and energy sector, inflation actually rose 0.5 percent. Inflation is the enemy of bonds, which pay fixed interest. The bond market reacted uncertainly to long-awaited reports on trade and factory output. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit narrowed in July to $ 7.58 billion, the smallest gap since December 1984. Output at the nation's factories, mines and utilities rose 0.3 percent in August. Several rumors of bad news also affected the market. Financial markets are susceptible to rumors because many people trade on them without taking time to see if they are true. By the end of the day traders decided that on balance the news was good. `` What the market got was kind of an information overload,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandross </PERSON>, economist for <ORGANIZATION> Lloyds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` Overall the economic numbers confirmed we're not in a recession and that growth is continuing at a respectable rate in the third quarter.'' Trading remained thin in the junk bond market, where lower-grade issues have been hit by the cash crunch at the <ORGANIZATION> Federated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Allied </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> units of Canadian retailing giant <ORGANIZATION> Campeau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. In the secondary market for <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> securities, prices of short-term governments were up about 1-32 point, intermediate maturities were up 3-32 to 3-16 point and long-term issues were up close to -LCB- point, according to <ORGANIZATION> Telerate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the financial information service. The movement of a point is equivalent to a change of $ 10 in the price of a bond with a $ 1,000 face value. The <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Bond Index, which measures price movements on all outstanding <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> issues with maturities of a year or longer, rose 1.89 to 1,183.49. <ORGANIZATION> Moody </ORGANIZATION>'s Investment Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures total return on a portfolio of 80 corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, gained 1.06 to 331.79. In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively traded municipal bonds fell 3-32 point to 92 11-16. The average yield to maturity rose to 7.36 percent from 7.35 percent late Thursday. Yields on three-month <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bills fell to 7.76 percent as the discount fell 5 basis points to 7.52 percent. Yields on six-month bills fell to 7.94 percent as the discount fell 2 basis points to 7.54 percent. Yields on one-year bills were unchanged at 7.98 percent as the discount remained at 7.45 percent. A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield is the annualized return on an investment in a <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bill. The discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face value, which is paid at maturity. The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, was quoted at 9 1-16 percent, up from 8 ~ percent late Thursday
