<SECOND>AM-McDonnell-Safety,0491</SECOND>
<HEAD>Douglas Makes Safety Modifications to DC-10s Following Freak Iowa
Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Friday it would modify its DC-10 jetliners to ensure safe landings even if all three hydraulic systems fail. The modifications, developed in response to a DC-10 crash that killed 112 people in <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, last July, were greeted warmly by <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Busey </PERSON>, the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. `` The system design changes proposed by <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> ... are a solid step forward in assuring there will be no repeat of the July 19 accident,'' <PERSON> Busey </PERSON> said in a statement issued in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> `` Once these design changes are in place, they will raise the already high safety standards required of the DC-10 and, in effect, make a good airplane even better.'' <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a division of <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> based in <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, manufactured the DC-10s, which have been replaced by the newer but similar MD-11s. <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Elayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Bendel </PERSON> said in a telephone interview that the company had yet to decide whether to make the same modifications to its MD-11s. `` We are going to look at the MD-11 and evaluate it and we'll do what is appropriate there,'' she said, `` and of course we will comply with whatever directives the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> issues.'' The three hydraulic systems on the planes are designed to be redundant, that is to operate independently and to back each other up in case one fails. In the July crash, the tail engine on the DC-10 disintegrated, knocking out all three hydraulic systems _ an event a <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> release Friday called `` one in a billion.'' The pilot lost virtually all control of the plane, which exploded in flames in a corn field near the runway. <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, a vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> who headed the investigation of the crash, said the following modifications will be made: _ An electrically operated shutoff valve will be installed in the supply line and a check valve in the return line of the No 3 hydraulic system. _ A check valve will be installed in the No 3 hydraulic reservoir. _ A cockpit light will be added to alert the crew if the shutoff valve is activated The new fast-acting shutoff valve, located just behind the back wall of the cabin, will close automatically and the cockpit light will come on if a sensor detects hydraulic fluid dropping below a preset level in the reservoir. Even if all three hydraulic systems are affected by severe damage to the tail section, as happened in <LOCATION> Sioux </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, the valve will stop fluid flow through the No. 3 system, <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> said. With adequate hydraulic pressure thus preserved in that system, the crew should have enough control to fly the plane to a safe landing.
