<HEAD>Judge Denies Injunction; Frees Universal to Pull Features</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A state judge on Friday refused to prevent <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Syndicate </ORGANIZATION> from pulling 26 comics and other features from the <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> until the newspaper's lawsuit against its main competitor is resolved. Judge <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> West </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> did not prove it would be irreparably harmed if it lost the features as a result of a deal between <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> A.H. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Belo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, parent company of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. `` They did n't prove to the judge's satisfaction that irreparable harm would take place and at the time of trial the <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> would likely prevail,'' <PERSON> West </PERSON> said. The order took effect immediately, but <PERSON> West </PERSON> said he would not hold the <ORGANIZATION> Times-Herald </ORGANIZATION> in contempt if some <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> features continue to appear in the newspaper for a few days. The judge said he realized some of the features were printed ahead of time and could n't immediately be withdrawn. A Universal Press official testified that The Morning News has agreed to run all 26 of the comics and columns in question, and <PERSON> Belo </PERSON> spokeswoman <PERSON> Jodie </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> said some of them will appear beginning Monday. `` We're very pleased with the decision, and now we can move on,'' Ms. <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> said. She declined further comment. <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> Editor <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bode </PERSON> said the newspaper will continue to pursue its antitrust case. `` We will fully and vigorously peruse all available legal remedies in an attempt to recover these features and all damages to the <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Bode </PERSON> said in a prepared statement. `` We will continue our suit and continue to fight for fair competition in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> with all our energies,'' he said. The judge issued his decision after attorneys asked him to indicate how he was leaning. He said that although he was ruling from the bench, he had given much thought to the decision. `` No one thinks a one-newspaper town is advantageous. I'm taking this very seriously,'' he said. He asked attorneys to agree on a trial date later this year for the antitrust suit and set a Nov. 6 hearing to decide whether the case should be transferred back to <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. `` I think the evidence overwhelmingly showed that this was a fantastic business opportunity for The Morning News,'' the paper's attorney, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Sims </PERSON>, said after the ruling The <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> suit accuses <PERSON> Belo </PERSON> of unfairly increasing its influence in the <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> media market. Belo last month formed a joint venture with <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City-based </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> to develop some of the syndicate's features for television. As part of the agreement, <PERSON> Belo </PERSON> _ which also owns <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>' top-rated TV station, <ORGANIZATION> WFAA </ORGANIZATION> _ acquired exclusive rights to <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> material Universal pulled its features from the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>, but the newspaper regained the right to print them under a temporary restraining order issued by West on Sept. 5.
