<HEAD>Filing Deadline For Plans To Take Over PSNH Passes; 4 Proposals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE RECHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The struggle over control of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION>'s largest electric utility settled on four companies Friday as the deadline passed for filing bankruptcy reorganization plans. <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hampshire </ORGANIZATION>, which filed for bankruptcy protection in January 1988, announced its plan to retain control Tuesday and formally filed the proposal with the bankruptcy court early Friday afternoon. Several hours later, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illuminating </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Connecticut </ORGANIZATION> became the fourth to add its name to the list. Northeast Utilities, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>'s largest electric utility, and <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Westborough </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, filed their plans earlier. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illuminating </ORGANIZATION> plan proposed a merger with <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, the only plan to do so. It also called for electricity rate increases of 5.5 percent a year for seven years for <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> customers, matching the rates proposed by <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utilities </ORGANIZATION> if <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> operates. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> plan called for increases of 4.8 percent during that period. New Hampshire Gov. <PERSON> Judd </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> endorsed the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> plan when it was introduced in July, but then switched allegiance this week to <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> because of the lower rates. But <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bayless </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> financial vice president, called his utility the favorite to retain control because its plan already has the approval of shareholders and creditors. <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> also needs only state regulators approval for its plan, he said. The other utilities still would have to reach agreement with shareholders and creditors, and get approval from the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, something <PERSON> Bayless </PERSON> said could prolong the bankruptcy case for two more years. The fact that <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>'s payoff to creditors and shareholders would be in securities while some of the other proposals offered cash or a combination did not deter <PERSON> Bayless </PERSON>. `` To our creditors, getting paper in April is a heckuva lot better than getting cash a year or two later,'' he said. The next step in the bankruptcy case will be hearings on the four plans, which federal bankruptcy Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Yacos </PERSON> hopes to conclude by mid-November. Then creditors and shareholders would vote on their choice, and <PERSON> Yacos </PERSON> would make the final decision. <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, with almost 400,000 customers, filed for bankruptcy under the burden of its 36 percent share of the $ 6.2 billion <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> nuclear plant. Negotiations have dragged on since then for a reorganization plan that would satisfy creditors, shareholders and the state. <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has the largest share of <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION>, which has been completed for three years, but has been unable to get a commercial operating license. United Illuminating's 17.5 percent is the second-largest share of <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> System </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION> own smaller shares. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Illuminating </ORGANIZATION> valued its plan at $ 2.2 billion, matching the value of the plan proposed by <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, regardless of whether <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> operates commercially. <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> placed a $ 2 billion value on its plan if <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> runs, $ 1.9 if it does not. Northeast valued its plan at $ 1.9 billion regardless.
