<FIRST>r f PM-AirFares     09-15 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Air Fares,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Airlines Raise Some Discount Fares</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: For Saturday PMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In an apparent effort to soften the impact of travel bargains offered to fall vacationers, several major airlines have raised a type of discount fare popular with business travelers. This past week the airlines hiked `` Supercoach'' one-way fares, favored by business fliers because they have more lenient advance-purchase requirements than cheaper discount fares and do n't require a Saturday-night stay The `` Supercoach'' fares, usually 15 percent to 40 percent below standard economy fares, were raised by around $ 20 for a one-way ticket. For example, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' lowest `` Supercoach'' fare from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> has been increased from $ 221 one way to $ 241. A three-day advance-purchase fare on <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> was boosted from $ 269 to $ 289. The action appears aimed at recovering part of the revenue lost from the big industrywide fare cuts for the fall season announced in mid-August. At that time, the carriers extended summer travel bargains and cut round-trip fares by as much as $ 160 to lure passengers in the historically weak autumn season. Most fares to <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> were reduced by $ 100 into next spring. But the latest increase's effect is akin to putting a finger in the dike, some analysts believe. `` The carriers are desperately trying to salvage a very serious problem that has occurred,'' said <PERSON> Julius </PERSON> <PERSON> Maldutis </PERSON>, who follows the airline industry for <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` They have had a massive erosion in yield. ... Any fare actions that are taken now are basically to stem the damage.'' An airline's yield, which reflects the average price of a ticket paid by a passenger for each mile flown, has become the name of the game in the competitive climate of the nation's airline industry. The increase was started by <ORGANIZATION> Midway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, an aggressive mid-sized carrier based in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> that is paying $ 210 million to buy 16 DC-9 aircraft, as well as gates and other airport facilities in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> from strikebound <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>. Midway upped its `` Supercoach'' fares Wednesday by $ 10 one way. The bigger carriers, including <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Trans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, quickly matched the move. But they raised the fares by $ 20. Some airlines raised `` Supercoach'' fares only in a few cities they serve to match competitors, while others made widespread boosts. <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Shipley </PERSON>, for example, said that carrier was increasing the fares in markets `` all over the country''. But Delta is making the change only `` in a very, very few selected markets,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lundy </PERSON>. Eastern is `` considering some selective increases,'' said spokesman <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, like <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> a subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, had proposed six weeks ago eliminating many `` Supercoach'' fares, but the move was n't matched by competitors and it dropped the idea. `` It was an effort on our part to simplify the one-way fare structure,'' said <PERSON> Ned </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
